@NODE "Mail_33" "Re: AMarquee"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Mon, 05 Jul 1999 15:32:50 +1200
Subject: Re: AMarquee
X-UIDL: 95952693c7b7101ad1f754363677bc69

On 04-Jul-99, Andrew Guard wrote:
> After reading about AMarquee in AF it seams the answer to pares.  No
> messing about UCD or TCP stuff.  No nead to worry about the
> bsdsocket.library (which isn't rather Amiga O/S like).

  Rick has said most of the important points already; AMarquee uses
TCP, which can be up to 10 times slower than UDP in lag times, that's
why I wrote my UDPFuncs, so you can write fast action net multiplayer
games. The other reason I didn't bother with it, is that you're relying
on someone else to for your multiplayer connection- what if the
programmer decides to go to the PC, and won't bother fixing a bug, or
won't update the code for OS5- then you're screwed!
  Anyway, it's easier to use my routines than Amarquee anyway, you only
need TCP-to-Blitz.lha from dev/basic on Aminet, and recompile your
Deflibs with bsdsocket.library1 in your amigalibs drawer in Blitzlibs: .
Hardly difficult (and you'd have to do that for the AMarquee lib
anyhow). All the login/disconnect code in my UDP_Funcs is already done,
and is virtually transparent to the program, with Amarquee you'd have
to do all the library calls to the lib, which would take much more work
than using my Funcs! 
  Another point is that if you want to do a multi-player game, you're
going to have to a lot of work yourself anyway to deal with lag, using
AI, velocity, time and acceleration calculations, that will be specific
to your game, and can't be made into generic routines :-/  So there's
no easy plugin solution for net games- you're going to have to do a
certain amount of hard work wether you like it or not! As they say- you
can't make babies without getting your Dick wet! 

> Have any of you got this working with Blitz, or better still any off
> you would wright lib for it.  I think it is going to be a bigger thing
> for Amiga programes then MUI has been!  
 
  Maybe only for Chess games ;-)

--
           Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
