Subject: Re: AMarquee
X-UIDL: 00e3d1a06c4668e9690f81a7a415e0af

On 06-Jul-99, Andrew Guard wrote:
> Well, well Rick Hodger, OK then but...
>> I watched as Andrew Guard hammered "AMarquee" out on their
>> keyboard...

>> After reading about AMarquee in AF it seams the answer to pares.  No
>> messing about UCD or TCP stuff.  No nead to worry about the
>> bsdsocket.library (which isn't rather Amiga O/S like).

>> But AFAIK AMarquee doesn't support UPD, plus it relies on the person
>> having AMarquee installed and working. Anyway, what's wrong with
>> bsdsocket.library? The only TCP/IP stacks that had a difference were
>> AS225 and KAQ9. And AFAIK, AS225 created socket.library. So where
>> exactly is the problem?
>> 

> UPD will be there in time. 

  You mean UDP.

> Why do the messing about whith something which is nothing like Amiga
> O/S way's of doing things.  bsdsocket.library is yestordays news, long
> live the king AMarquee, I say.

  Amarquee uses the bsdsocket.library!!

- Using Paul Burkey's Functions, what's so hard about:

    If ConnectTCP {Hostname,#PORT}  ; to initialise conection

    WriteTCP{&a$,Len(a$)}           ; to send a message

    a$=ReadTCP{}                    ; to Read a message

    CloseTCP{}                      ; to clean up 

  That's all there is to it!  The only handy thing about the Amarquee
lib, is the login\disconnect routines, which take a lot of work. My
functions do that too!

>  I rember ppl saying samething when MUI
> was young.  Why do all that work to do GUI when it so much simpler
> with MUI.  It's same with AMarquee. 
> I rather work on pointless things
> like game-play etc. 

  Yeah, that's why I released my Funcs to save people the hassle of
doing the net connection code- You can use UDP_Chat as the basic code
for your game- probably a lot easier than using Amarquee, and
having to convert C examples!   

> Also you problem about them having AMarquee on there system dosn't
> really hold up.  You can not run AmIRC, StrICQ, Voyager, IBrowse with
> out MUI on there system.  So following on, if they want to use my
> software on-line they will have to install AMarquee.  Simple.

   Lots of programs use MUI, only AmiComSys uses Amarquee AFAIK (and
AMarquee's been out for a year or so), and most people will be using
ICQ now instead as it has more features and is more flexible then
AmiComSys. Maybe more programs will use it- we'll have to see.
 
> Just give it a bit of time, it will happen AMarquee will be on every
> Amiga system.

  It depends wether he does the UDP support (he says he `might' do it)-
it involves a huge amount of extra work, and a complete re-organisation
of the code, as previously the TCP did all the checking/resend work.
  It has a sophisticated JAVA etc system, which may be good for normal
programs, but will the extra sophistication create extra lag- games
require simple and fast communications! For example, the small game
example given uses message ports, wouldn't going through this extra
layer add lag to the communications?    

-- 
