I watched as Andrew Guard hammered "Re: AMarquee" out on their keyboard...


> UPD will be there in time. 

I'll believe it when I see it.

> Why do the messing about whith something which is nothing like Amiga
> O/S way's of doing things.  bsdsocket.library is yestordays news, long
> live the king AMarquee, I say.  I rember ppl saying samething when MUI
> was young.  Why do all that work to do GUI when it so much simpler
> with MUI.  It's same with AMarquee.  I rather work on pointless things
> like game-play etc.  

> Also you problem about them having AMarquee on there system dosn't
> really hold up.  You can not run AmIRC, StrICQ, Voyager, IBrowse with
> out MUI on there system.  So following on, if they want to use my
> software on-line they will have to install AMarquee.  Simple.

> Now of couse you don't have to have MUI, but you lose all best On-Line
> software if you don't.

> Just give it a bit of time, it will happen AMarquee will be on every
> Amiga system.

I doubt it.  AMarquee has been around for a long time now (about 2 years I
think), and the only decent program that you can use it with is a shareware
ICQ clone.  But there are some things that just are not going to be
possible to do with AMarquee, and that's why you have bsdsocket.library -
send a ICMP Ping packet with AMarquee...go on...or what about that
wonderful, limit-the-number-of-connections option? Suppose you ran FTP,
IRC, and ICQ....if the user has limited it to 5 connections that's it, he
can't do anymore (FTP needs 2, IRC needs 1 provided you don't use DCC or
plus 1 if you use IdentD, ICQ needs a UDP connection as well as multiple
TCP connections...) 

AMarquee is good for people who only want to do simple, basic TCP/IP
communications...try to do anything complicated and you need to use
bsdsocket.library.

-- 
