From: Jonas Thorell <jonasth@bahnhof.se>
        Blitz-List <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS Partner
X-UIDL: 62929fe4b4bd8467cc8d0f42cdee13ae



On Mon, 12 Jul 1999, Anton Reinauer wrote:

>   I don't know much about Linux etc, but the ports to Amiga of programs
> like GhostScript, UNLZX-PPC, LHA-PPC all seem to be rather crappy,
> unstable, and /very/ inefficient- LHA-PPC on my 200mhz 603e runs about
> the same speed as the assem coded LHA on the 25/040!!
>   Wether this is a general feature of Linux/Unix programming I don't
> know, but it's rather worrying :-/  

It's not - it's a feature you get when you port programs the wrong
way. There's more to porting a Linux C++ program than to make sure
you have the correct include files + GCC installed and to type
make in a shell...and I wonder what the purpose of porting Lha
to PPC is, since the decoding part of the 68k version runs from
within the cache. Lha in itself isn't the bottleneck in other words,
it's the disk I/O. 

>I wonder wether they bother writing
>efficient programs, as Unix boxes are so grunty.

Run Gimp under Linux and then compare it to Photoshop 5 running
under Windows on the same hardware and you realise they do.

/Jonas


