@NODE "Mail_57" "Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS Partner"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Mon, 12 Jul 1999 19:33:19 +0100
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS Partner
X-UIDL: 89f055d803287358a7f76162d3243045

I watched as Frederic Laboureur hammered "Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS
Partner" out on their keyboard...

>> It's not - it's a feature you get when you port programs the wrong
>> way. There's more to porting a Linux C++ program than to make sure
>> you have the correct include files + GCC installed and to type
>> make in a shell...and I wonder what the purpose of porting Lha
>> to PPC is, since the decoding part of the 68k version runs from
>> within the cache. Lha in itself isn't the bottleneck in other words,
>> it's the disk I/O. 

>     Just 2 precisions, if the 68k Lha run within the cache, why no the PPC
> one as the PPC has much bigger and faster cache than any 68k ? And BTW,
> is Lha PPC doing 3 Mb/s for decompression ? The Disk I/O can't be the
> bottleneck, else do a raw read into the Memory and decompress later...

You're looking at raw statistics.  For a start, the Amiga has a notoriously
bad IDE interface that chews up CPU like there's no tomorrow.  This means
that although some Amiga's may get somewhere in the region of 5mb/s, when I
originally got my first hard-disk, the most I could ever get was about
500kb/s.

Next, you have to consider that when you want to process a file (in *any*
way) using the PPC, you have to first load it in using the 68k routines in
the OS and then transfer it to an area of memory that is set-up for the PPC
to use.  Once done, with the file, the PPC has to put the data back to
somewhere were the 68k OS routines can access it and write it to a file.

Essentially, it doesn't matter how fast the processor is that does the
processing, it could be a PIII overclocked to 1 Ghz, it's still going to be
brought down to less than a couple of hundred kb/s by the OS.

-- 
