@NODE "Mail_58" "Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS Partner"
Date: 12 Jul 99 22:48:10 +0100
From: "Jonas Thorell" <jonasth@bahnhof.se>
Subject: Re: Amiga DUMP QNX as the OS Partner
encoding: 7bit
X-System: Amiga 3000/040@40 Mhz, 99 Meg, 11.5 Gig HD, 28k8
X-Hardware: Prelude soundcard, Vlab digitizer, CV64 gfx-card
X-Hardware: Buddha IDE-controller, 24x CD-ROM
X-Software: Aweb, Miami, Thor, ScalOS, MCP and assorted bits of bytes...
X-UIN: 12427044
X-Misc-info: Who's reading this??
X-UIDL: 04b76858ee1e7aca15c4a2e7db0bf270

Frederic Laboureur (alphasnd@sdv.fr) wrote:

>Just 2 precisions, if the 68k Lha run within the cache, why no the
>PPC one as the PPC has much bigger and faster cache than any 68k ? 

Most likely because of the one thing that makes the PowerUP cards less
fast than they should have to be: the dreaded cpu-switch, which
requires the caches to be emptied. LhaPPC starts to decrompress something,
oops - we need the 68k to write to disk - a switch to 68k. Then we need to
continue the real work, oh - switch back to the PPC ad infinitum. Hope
you get the picture. It most certainly is possible to avoid that situation
but just compiling the lha.c won't do it.

Okay, that's how I've interpreted the whole thing. Might be wrong, but
that doesn't matter since the crux of the matter is: it's unfair to judge
an OS becuase some programs from it have been ported poorly. It's not just the Amiga
that's fallen prey to that either. I was playing around with the software
to a Diamond RIO-mp3 portable player today. The software shipped with it (Win98)
worked flawlessly, but I decided I wanted to try the version that's floating around
the Internet as well. Worked a whole lot worse, despite it having a feature not found
on the original one. It worked, but I got a lot of transfer errors (for those that
do not know, the software allows you to transfer mp3-files over a parallell-cable to
the player). But that software was also a direct Linux-port. I bet that it would
have worked much better if it had taken Windows into consideration.

If anyone's up for a challenge, I have the source-code here if someone wants to
do a proper Amiga-port of it.

>And BTW, is Lha PPC doing 3 Mb/s for decompression ? 

Haven't measured. The bottleneck was more the 68k on the "normal" lha.

>The Disk I/O can't be the bottleneck, 

Maybe not, and to be honest, I think Bobergs old but venerable lha is
as optimised as need be and I can't for the life of me figure out why
a PPC version would be needed. The day (as if) the whole OS is PPC-native,
yes. Not today. And much of the PPC software on Aminet falls into that
trap, compiled for PPC just because the PPC is there. No second thought 
over if it's justified or not. 

>else do a raw read into the Memory and decompress
>later...

Sure, which is why a straight forward recompilation of a Unix program
usually is a bad idea. You need to take the platform-specifics into
account.

>Linux progs aren't bad, it's just the Graphical interface which
>isn't unique, 

WIMPS are for loosers...What's wrong with ksh and Vi...

>so you don't have a standard which is boring: you have good
>software on many enviromment, so you have to restart you X-Server
>each time :-).

No, you don't. X is X is X. KDE or Enlightment doesn't matter, the software
will run (granted, it sometimes needs some tinkering).

Enough with the off-topic rambling already...

