  That's true, from their point of view.  They never even supported the
Amiga on their sight.  In fact, it was almost as if they considered the
Amiga an embarassment, with virtually no mention of it at all.  They
considered the Amiga OS they were supposed to be working just a
relitively unimportant sideline, and were puttion no special priority
on it.  That is one of the main reasons why Amiga began looking around
again.  QNX is a respectable OS by a respectable company, but a company
which felt no special affinity to the Amiga nor any special obligation
to accomplish the needed work in the time-frame available, let alone
any need to put any effort into advertising or even acknowledging the
partnership.

  I would have been happy to use an Amiga OS based on QNX, but I am
not dismayed at the switch to Linux, especially as it offers some
advantages not available with QNX.  QNX may be somewhat more polished
at this time but Linux is gaining very fast and believe will soon surpass
QNX even in this area.



cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



