On 20-Jul-99, Mikkel Lřkke flashed:
>Hello James.

>So I guess I'm not the only one who can't see the "Revolutionary" aspect of
>using PCI lots and Ultra DMA IDE, when PC's are moving towards AGP and Ultra2
>SCSI. And Mac's toward Firewiwre.

>I say we get an AMiGA with SBus slots, and Fibre Channel. It ould fit much
>better into what Jim Collas actually has planned for the AMiGA.

>IDE sucks. I'm not gonna by the stupid thing until I can get a driver for
>RaidTEC FC-AL 19" racks. So there.




  Actually, the new Amigas will have USB and Firewire, which is not to bad a
way to go, and indeed is exactly where Macs are moving to now.  I personally
would like to see up-to-date SCSI standard also but I doubt that will happen.
IDE is not to bad for everyday mass storage hard-drives, but I also am not
that in love with it, it does suck for most other things.  And I agree,
Fibre Channel would be cool.
  I believe some of those things are actually in the plans for a little
later on.  The first of the new Amigas will doubtless not be as cool as the
ones to follow, but isn't that allways the way it is as technology moves
forward?  I will probably buy one of the first of the new Amigas because I
need a new machine and because they will doubtless be more cool than anything
else on the market even if they aren't perfect.  I operate and service the
very latest Macs and wintels at work and both operating systems are becoming
more and more of a nightmare, bloated, innefficiant and full of bugs.  The
Mac OS didn't use to be that bad but it is getting more and more like windoz
all the time.  It's a constant barrage of upgrading, paying more money, lack
of support for hugely expensive software and everone blaming everyone else
for the clashes and incompatabilities.  I'm really getting fed up.  I want
new Amigas at work AND at home!  Even if the new Amiga OS isn't as lean as
the old one, it simply CAN'T be anywhere near as bad as the alternatives,
which make no attempt or pretense of staying lean, clean and mean.


  I actually have high hopes for the new Amigas even though I will also
probably be able to think of things I would like to improve on them.  But
that's what third partys, new models, hacking and hot-rodding are for.

  It's going to be a fun ride!



cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



