Hi David

On 23-Jul-99, David McMinn wrote:
> Hi again,
> 
> If I wanted to convert case of a character, including non-English
> characters (i.e. accented chars, Russian, Greek, etc), would it be as
> simple as this (for upper->lower case):
> 
> If (character is between 65 and 90) or (character is between 192 and 223)
>    Bitwise OR 32 with character code
> End If
> 
> I know the normal letters are between 65 and 90 and that accented are
> between 192 and 223, as well as some other letters on this font map I'm
> looking at, but I don't know where letters from totally different
> languages are, like Russian, Greek, etc.
> 
> Using locale.library is not an option.
> 
> Any help would cure some annoyance.

^^^^ Famous last words :)

If you have a recent copy of My Crazy8's game, look
in it's "Fonts/" drawer.  There is a standard font (with the normal "alt"
characters) and a couple of other fonts (sent to me by the translators)
that are used with some of the translations.

One is a standard font used for Polish - if you examine it, you will find
that
not only are some of the "alt" characters different, but also some of the
"alt" characters are the same as in a standard "English" font, but moved to
different locations.

In other words, there isn't necessarily an uppercase and a directly
co-responding lower case symbol for each "alt" character like there is for
"M" and "m"...

Although what you suggested would work in most cases, there would be
exceptions.

As far as Russian, Greek, etc...  I imagine the whole thing would be
completely different, on a case by case basis...

And now, can I ruin anybody else's day for them?  ;)

Later...
-- 


