@NODE "Mail_141" "Re: Collision Detection"
From: "Vic E Babes" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Collision Detection
Date: Fri, 9 Jul 1999 20:12:22 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 465e13898220815c85929f4dccf8119e

Wiremu wrote,

> Yeah, what's the best way to do it with the Blitter?  I'm fiddling with a
> program that uses BlitCol(?) and the like but its collision detection is
far
> from perfect; especially with LARGE blits.

It depends what type of game your doing, for example - the 4-player game
that I`m writing at the moment can`t use this method, but, for example, it
is perfect for a Mario-clone.

You should change the handle of the shapes that represent the human player,
to the bottom-right corner - or somewhere appropriate (which I`ll get to).
Then you can simply write a routine like the following:

    If PlayerX > ComX
        If PlayerX < (ComX + (#Playwisth+#ComWidth))
            If PlayerY > ComY
                If PlayerY < (Comy + (#PlayHeight + #ComHeight))
                    Then shapes have collided.
                Endif
            Endif
        Endif
    Endif

The problem that I think you are experiencing is that shapes are rarely
rectangles, and so it appears to the player that there hasn`t been a
collision, because - although the rectangles overlap, the graphics do not.
For example, imagine you have a 16x16 shape, the top 4 pixels of which
consist of a single spike sticking up from the centre - the shapes would not
look as though they had collided if the other shape was to the left or right
of this spike -

- so the best thing to do here, assuming the spikey shape is a bady - is to
move the HANDLE down 4 pixels, and state that the shape is actually 4 pixels
shorter than it really is for the constant #ComHeight.

Or for a better example, my character`s head is 16 pixels wide, but his body
is only 12, and I didn`t want a collision detected for 2 pixels on either
side of him.  He is also 32 pixels high - so i moved the HANDLE to 13,31, so
that the hotspot (as with your mouse pointer)  would be at the bottom right
of his feet.  I also stated in the constant, that #PlayWidth was 12.

You can also improve the above routine to detect which parts of the shapes
collided - so for a Mario clone, I wanted to know if George had jumped on a
baddy or walked into one - so:


    If PlayerX > ComX
        If PlayerX < (ComX + (#Playwisth+#ComWidth))
            If PlayerY > ComY
                If PlayerY < (Comy + (#PlayHeight + #ComHeight))
                    If (PlayerY < (ComY + 2)) AND Falling
                        Then George jumped on Baddy
                    Else
                        Baddy got George
                    Endif
                Endif
            Endif
        Endif
    Endif

Where falling is a flag set earlier on to state whether George was walking
jumping or falling.  The above code was typed in my e-mail thing by the way,
so there could be an error in it.

Routine works wonderfully.

VIC




