Hi Oliver

On 24-Jul-99, Oliver Marks wrote:
> Hi,
> 
>> > 
>> > I am havind trouble with copy mem can anyone see what is wrong with
>> > the code below it dowes not like copying the memory to a newtype is
>> > there any reason for this?
>> > 
>> > NEWTYPE.ChunkyPort
>> > cp_Identifier.l         ; == CHKP ###
>> > *cp_Chunky.b            ; Memory allocated for the chunky data
>> > cp_cx.w                 ; Draw pen x position in buffer
>> > cp_cy.w                 ; Y pen
>> > cp_APen.b               ; Foreground pen
>> > cp_OPen.b               ; Outline pen
>> > cp_BPen.b               ; Background pen
>> > cp_IPen.b               ; Shine/shadow pen
>> > cp_Flags.w ; Flags which are the same as graphics/rastport.h
>> > *cp_Font.TextFont       ; Font to use for text rendering
>> > *cp_TxtChunky.b ; Chunky data buffer used for text rendering ###
>> > cp_TxHeight.w           ; Height of the text ###
>> > cp_TxBaseline.w         ; Baseline of the text ###
>> > cp_TxStyle.w            ; Softstyles in graphics/text.h plus these...
>> > cp_NoFree.w ; TRUE if buffer was grabbed from a memory location
>> > cp_BufSize.l            ; Number of bytes used for cp_Chunky
>> > cp_Width.w              ; Pixel width of buffer
>> > cp_Height.w             ; Pixel height of buffer
>> > *cp_Colours.ColoursCP ; Pointer to colour palete data or NULL if none
>> > *cp_ScrollCP.ChunkyPort ; @{bg shine}(V4)@{bg background} Used by
>> >  cp_Reserved.l[7]       ; ###
>> > End NEWTYPE
>> > 
>> > 
>> > *srp=ViewPort(0)
>> > *cmem.l=AllocMem_(320*200,#MEMF_ANY)
>> > If (BLoad("/_shared/320x200.chk",cmem))
>> >   cp=CHK_InitChunky_(320,200)
>> >   ColourPalette = CHK_LoadRGB32_(cp,"/_shared/320x200.col")
>> > CopyMem_ cmem,cp\cp_Chunky,(320*200)
>> >   CHK_ChooseHardwareMode_(&SCRtags(0));
>> >   CHK_DrawChunky_ cp, srp, 0, 0
>> > EndIf
>> > 
>> > If anyone can see any other obvious error let me know as a lot of this
>> > is knew to me i am new at dealing with chunky bitmaps and displays and
>> > how does Bload work does it just load in the file as is ?

The Bload command is weird - it can load into a bank (whatever that is), or
memory you have allocated depending on the parameters.  But I would suggest
just allocating the memory yourself with Allocmem_ and then use WriteMem to
load in the file.

The only difference is that you must free the memory when you are done with
it.

Or better yet (unless there is some reason you are loading the chunky data
into one place in memory, then copying it into another) why not just initial
the chunky buffer first, then use writemem to load the chunky data directly
into it.

> 
> CopyMem_ cmem,cp\cp_Chunky,(320*200)
> the above line of code bring up a syntax error when copying to a
> newtype any ideas why. ?

cmem should be initialized as a pointer, not a long:  *cmem  not  cmem.l
It seems like it would be the same thing, but remember Blitz treats plain
longs as signed.

*Also I don't think cp_Chunky.b should *be a byte.  It must be pointing to a
memory location where the chunky data is, right?  How can you do that with
one byte?

I think that might be the main problem.

And when allocating or copying memory, you should use a long as the number
of bytes needed:

needmem.l=320*200
CopyMem_ *mem,cp\cp_Chunky,needmem

Later...
-- 


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



