>>> > If anyone can see any other obvious error let me know as a lot of this
>>> > is knew to me i am new at dealing with chunky bitmaps and displays and
>>> > how does Bload work does it just load in the file as is ?
> 
> The Bload command is weird - it can load into a bank (whatever that is),

Actually, its not a bank as in the way Amos treats Banks, its just
a memory area, the only things BLoad does over AllocMem() is A,
load in a file after it has AllocMem()`ed. And B, always free the
memory on exit regardless of wheather you forget.

InitBank() is the same as AllocMem() except InitBank() will free mem 
on exit. 

The Bank commands are just easier ways of getting files into mem,
and allocating mem.

But you already knew all that.

> or memory you have allocated depending on the parameters. But I would
> suggest just allocating the memory yourself with Allocmem_ and then use
> WriteMem to load in the file.

Or AllocMem() ;)

> The only difference is that you must free the memory when you are done
> with it.

Yup.

> Or better yet (unless there is some reason you are loading the chunky data
> into one place in memory, then copying it into another) why not just
> initial the chunky buffer first, then use writemem to load the chunky data
> directly into it.

Dont you mean ReadMem? Or am I confused? ;)

>> 
>> CopyMem_ cmem,cp\cp_Chunky,(320*200)
>> the above line of code bring up a syntax error when copying to a
>> newtype any ideas why. ?
> 
> cmem should be initialized as a pointer, not a long:  *cmem  not  cmem.l
> It seems like it would be the same thing, but remember Blitz treats plain
> longs as signed.

Yup, didn`t notice that one ;)

> *Also I don't think cp_Chunky.b should *be a byte. It must be pointing to
> a memory location where the chunky data is, right? How can you do that
> with one byte?

Nah, thats not the problem, if it`s a pointer it doesn`t matter if it`s
assigned as a byte.

> I think that might be the main problem.

No,.. NIMO ;)

> And when allocating or copying memory, you should use a long as the number
> of bytes needed:
> 
> needmem.l=320*200
> CopyMem_ *mem,cp\cp_Chunky,needmem

yeah that could cause problems. :)

