> 
>> A1400T AGA NTSC (no GFX card)
> 
>> ScreenMode NTSC hi-res-laced:            715909
> 
>> Degrader 50HZ (screenmode goes to PAL)   715909
> 
>> Degrader 50HZ 50HZSystem                 715909
> 
>> In other words, it's always the same, no matter what I do to the
>> screen.
> 
>  Yeah, I get the same same on my PAL machine- just the tics/sec is
> 709379 instead. If I boot up in NTSC mode I get 709379 for every screen
> wether it's PAL or NTSC :-/ That must mean that the #Ticks# command is
> a Vblank timer not the EClock!

Yes, the Ticks command gives me 60 per second on an NTSC screen, and 50 on a
PAL.
But I can't use any other screenmodes on my system, so I have no idea what
happens if a different screen mode other than a NTSC or PAL mode is used...

>  Hmmm, I'll have to have a think some more- maybe checking the screen
> height- wether it's 200 or 400 for NTSC, or 256 and 512 for PAL
> (overscan would screw that up though :-/ ). Or maybe using the EClock
> to compare the time (short term) in case the user has changed screens.
> Apparantly the EClock isn't so good for long term timers, so I can't
> use that :-/

I'm assuming this is for your tcp-linked game?  What about using a "master"
clock on one machine, using the EClock.  You could also use the EClock on
the other machines, but periodically send an update signal to reset the
rest of them - like those clock systems used in schools and hospitals.

That way, any inaccuracies would be universal to all the players - maybe
that would be good enough?

Forgive me if this idea is totally unworkable - I don't know much about TCP
stuff... 
> 
Later...
-- 

