@NODE "Mail_190" "Re: Eclock and device functions (Was Re: NTSC)"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 07 Jul 1999 19:49:26 +1200
Subject: Re: Eclock and device functions (Was Re: NTSC)
X-UIDL: 6a90dee50724228dd6b1bc4cb2f6ea69

On 06-Jul-99, Curt Esser wrote:
 
>>> A1400T AGA NTSC (no GFX card)
>> 
>>> ScreenMode NTSC hi-res-laced:            715909
>> 
>>> Degrader 50HZ (screenmode goes to PAL)   715909
>> 
>>> Degrader 50HZ 50HZSystem                 715909
>> 
>>> In other words, it's always the same, no matter what I do to the
>>> screen.

>> Yeah, I get the same same on my PAL machine- just the tics/sec is
>> 709379 instead. If I boot up in NTSC mode I get 709379 for every
>> screen wether it's PAL or NTSC :-/ That must mean that the #Ticks#
>> command is a Vblank timer not the EClock!

> Yes, the Ticks command gives me 60 per second on an NTSC screen, and
> 50 on a PAL.
> But I can't use any other screenmodes on my system, so I have no idea
> what happens if a different screen mode other than a NTSC or PAL mode
> is used...

 Some people tried it out on their GFX cards- it used the NTSC/PAL rate
not the GFX card rate, so the Vblank/Ticks must run off the CIA chip
(there's a listing of a VBlank timer in the CIA hardware docs).

>> Hmmm, I'll have to have a think some more- maybe checking the screen
>> height- wether it's 200 or 400 for NTSC, or 256 and 512 for PAL
>> (overscan would screw that up though :-/ ). Or maybe using the EClock
>> to compare the time (short term) in case the user has changed
>> screens. Apparantly the EClock isn't so good for long term timers, so
>> I can't use that :-/

> I'm assuming this is for your tcp-linked game? What about using a
> "master" clock on one machine, using the EClock. You could also use
> the EClock on the other machines, but periodically send an update
> signal to reset the rest of them - like those clock systems used in
> schools and hospitals.

  Yes, I was going to do this anyway, as a backup measure :-) 

> That way, any inaccuracies would be universal to all the players -
> maybe that would be good enough?
  
  Well the problem is you have inaccuracies caused by the lag times
anyway, so any extra inaccuracies will make the problem worse :-/
   If I can guarantee all the machines are running the same time (well
close enough anyway), then I can send out player's positions, speed,
etc with a timestamp so each machine can then calculate where that
player should be. This way the player is in the same place on all
machines at the same time (after maybe things like artificial speed ups
to get it to the correct place). So any significant difference in times
between machines could cause major problems :-/
  I'm thinking of using the Vblank with the EClock (or CIA timer)
running as well, to double check for any irregularities- like a PAL
screen on an NTSC machine.  

> Forgive me if this idea is totally unworkable - I don't know much
> about TCP stuff...
 
  Nah, I'm going to see how inaccurate the EClock is anyway :)  But the
other major problem with it, is another program can change the Eclock's
value- which would screw it up completely! :-/

  Seeya- Anton

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
