@NODE "Mail_203" "File to Newtype"
From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 20 Jul 99 11:43:39 +1000
Subject: File to Newtype
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: e5d3c19851cfca5ca1fe5dfab8150699

I'm trying to speed up random file access when loading it into a
Linked list (Either a Blitz List or Dave's DLL)

What I'm doing at the moment is the usual open the file, define Fields
statements define a newtype for the list entry, and loop through doing
Additem, read a record, move all fields into my newtype.

What I'd really like to do is to define the newtype to match the
layout in the file record and do a ReadMem into the newtype.

So... If I have all numeric fields there's no real problem.  I just do
something like

newtype.Rec1
a.l
b.l
c.l
end newtype

deftype.rec1 *Record1

then ReadMem into &*Record1\a

However, with string variables, I can't read the address of the
string.

What I guess I need to do is

Newtype .rec2
a.l
String.s
String_Length.l
Chars.b[maxlen of string]
b.l
end newtype

deftype .rec2 *Record2

then if I Readmem into &*Record2
can I simply do Poke.l(&*Record2\String,  &Record2\String_Length) and
then use the string as usual.    That syntax may not be right, but any
ideas would be appreciated.   When I rewrite the file, it saves the
address to disk, but that will be meaningless next time it is read in.
I'm not too bothered about a 4-byte overhead on disk, speed of loading
is much more important to me.

Thanks for any ideas

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+4Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater

