For additional commands, e-mail: blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_204" "Re: File to Newtype"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 20 Jul 1999 14:30:39 +0100
Subject: Re: File to Newtype
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 22228f5b09b84680da9980da2d5143a7


> deftype.rec1 *Record1
> 
> then ReadMem into &*Record1\a

well, technicall you'd have to allocate memory for the pointer first, or guru.

> What I guess I need to do is
> 
> Newtype .rec2
> a.l
> String.s
> String_Length.l
> Chars.b[maxlen of string]
> b.l
> end newtype

Yep, you'll definately need to include the string data in the newtype like 
that. I don't think there is any easy way to force Blitz to use that array as 
the string though, i.e. if you do String = "jfus" later, it will use a 
different memory location. You might need to go through your list copying all 
the strings into the arrays before writing. And when reading back in you may be 
able to work it as you done below (just poking the address of the array into 
the string variable) but Blitz might try to free the array if you assign the 
String to something else. If that happens you might need to do a 
String=Peek$(array) after reading everything in.


-- 
