@NODE "Mail_205" "Re: File to Newtype"
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: File to Newtype
Date: Tue, 20 Jul 1999 16:28:50 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: e5408f01c97cfd6900f6fcb8a6acbd02

Hi,

>However, with string variables, I can't read the address of the
>string.
>
>What I guess I need to do is
>
>Newtype .rec2
>a.l
>String.s
>String_Length.l
>Chars.b[maxlen of string]
>b.l
>end newtype
>
>deftype .rec2 *Record2
>
>then if I Readmem into &*Record2
>can I simply do Poke.l(&*Record2\String,  &Record2\String_Length) and
>then use the string as usual.    That syntax may not be right, but any
>ideas would be appreciated.   When I rewrite the file, it saves the
>address to disk, but that will be meaningless next time it is read in.
>I'm not too bothered about a 4-byte overhead on disk, speed of loading
>is much more important to me.


The problem with that is that the \String is only a longword pointer to a
string and not the actual string itself (when you do a readmem it simple
reads directly into the memory) so it wouldn`t be correct to do that. And
the length of the string, and maxlength of the string are stored -4, and -8
from the string pointer, so that is going to give you lots of headaches.

>Thanks for any ideas


I think the only answer would be to hardcode the file using
writemem/readmem, there are somethings you need to watch though...

newtype .rec
                                ;offset
    a.l                        ;0
    b.l                        ;4
    c.l                        ;8
    string1.s            ;12   - these have to have been maxlen`d
    string2.s            ;16

end newtype


You need the numbers first...basically your you`d simply store each record
at a fixed size, and then just multiply by the item number you want to get
the position

to write an item you`d do something like

writemem 0,&currentitem,12                                    ;write the
numbers out
writemem 0,currentitem\string1,maxlenstring1        ;write string1 out
writemem 0,currentitem\string2,maxlenstring2        ;write string2 out

Then to read it in, you`d add a new item and maxlen currentitem\string1 and
\string2 and then do readmems.

The only thing with that is there would be some space wasted (maxlen
strings). You could only save the length of the string..but then you need to
have a table of offsets of items and it becomes more complicated. And you`d
have to do create a new file everytime the database was modified (better
anyway...ever crashed in the middle of a save when it`s writing back to the
same database?? better to write to a temp file, then once that`s safe delete
the database and rename the temp file)

Anyway...hope some of that made sense...

Dave


