@NODE "Mail_207" "Re: File to Newtype"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 20 Jul 1999 17:26:27 -0500
Subject: Re: File to Newtype
X-UIDL: b9c0f010c4e524b80ba6ef2f0756aa3e

Hi Tony

On 19-Jul-99, Tony Rolfe wrote:
> I'm trying to speed up random file access when loading it into a
> Linked list (Either a Blitz List or Dave's DLL)

> What I'd really like to do is to define the newtype to match the
> layout in the file record and do a ReadMem into the newtype.
> 
> So... If I have all numeric fields there's no real problem.  I just do
> something like
> 
> newtype.Rec1
> a.l
> b.l
> c.l
> end newtype
> 
> deftype.rec1 *Record1
> 
> then ReadMem into &*Record1\a
> 
> However, with string variables, I can't read the address of the
> string.

> Thanks for any ideas

OK, here's a crazy one - HEY!  Sometimes my crazy ideas do work  ;)

This is only appropriate if your strings have a preset maximum length?

If this is true, let's use for example a string with a maximum length of 31
characters.  But, forget about characters - it's 32 bytes we need to store,
right?
(31 ascii characters and a chr$(0))

So, we make our NewType:

NewType.record1
  string.l     ;8 bytes
  morestring.l ;8 bytes
  morestr2.l   ;8 bytes
  morestr3.l   ;8 bytes
End NewType

Now, the string IS stored directly in the NewType (although Blitz doesn't
know it's a string) - and of course you can add other actual numeric
variables to it, or even more "hidden strings".

So, you can ReadMem and WriteMem them as you like.

To actually display them on the screen, you would use Peek.s(record1\string)
and to work on them as strings, you would copy them into an actual string,
do your editing using the regular string commands, then Poke.s it back into
the NewType.

Well, you did say ANY ideas...

-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



