@NODE "Mail_227" "Goodrats... err... mice"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 10 Jul 1999 08:43:09 +0500
Subject: Goodrats... err... mice
X-UIDL: 31a117012b580af802029bebdbee4d38

On 09-Jul-99, Rick Hodger flashed:

>>  By the way, does anyone here have any Golden Image OPTICAL mice they
>> want to sell?

>I have one, but one of the LED's in it died about 3 years ago, and none of
>the electrical suppliers around here have any idea what to replace it with,
>apparently a standard red LED is too big, and produces the wrong kind of
>light :/


  These LEDs are a standard size, 5mm sometimes called T1.  The trick is
that they must be Infra-Red LEDs which look like clear LEDs but aren't.
Sometimes Tandy/Radio Shack carry them.  It is super simple to solder one
in, just dont overheat the board leads.

  It is a combination of the use of Infra-Red LEDs and a lens focusing
system which makes the Golden Image optical mice so good.

  Are you sure that an LED is bad though?  LEDs almost never go bad unless
fed with to much voltage which should never happen if you only plug the
mouse into the Amiga mouse port (you didn't plug it into a 9 pin VGA
monitor port on some wintel machine did you?   ;)     Just kidding!
  You can check the LEDs by looking very closely at them in a dark room
while the mouse is powered.  They will be glowing with a very faint red
light if they are working.  The Infra-Red light is far to weak to harm
your eyes, being MUCH less than the IR content in natural sunlight
reflected off a matt-finish surface.
  Remember, just because the LEDs dont glow doesn't necessarily mean
they are bad.  It is quite common for a lead to crack loose from the
solder at the board, or the plug-in connector for the cord to the board
to loose contact due to looseness or oxidation.  Fortunately, oxidation
is not generally a problem on Golden Image mice as they use gold-plated
connectors, but wiggle it anyway.
  By far the most common problem however is for a lead to break within
the cord right where it goes into the case, interupting either the power
to the LEDs or the return signal from one of them (causing the mouse to
respond on only one axis, horizontally or vertically).  The cord can be
shortened about 10 or 12 cm and re-applied.

  This was one of only two weak points of the Golden Image optical mice:
There is no strain relief where the cord enters the case of the mouse.
The other is that the buttons break loose where they are gluet to the
case-top which is easily fixed with common model cement (just be careful
not to get it in the wrong place or use to much).
  The button switches are a common industry standard and easily replaced
if needed.


  By the way, much of this applies to most opti-mechanical mice also.


Sorry about the rather longish off-topic post, but I figured that someone
else may be in the same boat.


  If you want to sell yours as is, email me privatly.



cacha later,

