@NODE "Mail_229" "Re: Goodrats... err... mice"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 10 Jul 1999 19:51:49 +0500
Subject: Re: Goodrats... err... mice
X-UIDL: a28ff05ee22382117052ad35a07959d0

On 11-Jul-99, Rick Hodger flashed:


>Hmm....I'm beginning to wonder about this, no gold-plated connectors
>whatsoever....but it has the Golden Image logo printed on the mouse itself.

>The LED's were soldered in series on mine, stretching the remaining working
>one across the two holders and it works fine :(

>Maybe I got a wierd one?  I'd send a pic of it, but it's buried in the "big
>pile of dead 'puter bits" in the corner...way too warm to go searching...


  It sounds like you have one of their early versions maybe.  I can't say
for sure 'cause I bought all three of mine just before they dissapeared
from the market.  Mine are model GI-6000 serial numbered in the 621050--
range and made in Taiwan by Jin Tech (the name is molded right into the
left side of the case).  Yours sounds suspiciously like the Alpha-Data
optical mouse (which I also have one of but never use).  The A-D ones
read a square grid like most others instead of reading dots (or most
any other pattern or bumps) like the Golden Image 6000 does.
The Alpha-Data ones also have a wierd, overly complex arrangement of two
small LEDs (which glow a very bright red) wired in series and mounted high
above the bottom of the mouse, which shine down through a wierd L shaped
the bottom of the case.  The reflected light is channeled up through two
large, bulbous lenses (which look like clear LEDs but aren't) and way up to
the top where it is reflected by two mirrors down through two cardboard
light-shields onto two receptors.  The whole thing is rather large, clumsey
and poorly engineered, hard to work on and easy to knock out of kilter.
  The Golden Image mice on the other hand use two clear infra-red LEDs
mounted right down at the bottom of the case and the reflected light merely
goes up through a single very small lens to a single receptor chip, no
mirrors or magic needed.  It is virtually impossible to knock them out of
kilter and the mechanism is so small and simple that the case is almost
empty.  Also, due to this arrangement they will read properly an amazing
distance above the surface (great for playing things like Shuffle-Puc
Cafe where you get excited and tend to lift the mouse a bit off the
surface, thus making play a lot more fun and natural).
  It makes me sick that the buying public got burned by the crummy optical
mice befor the GI-6000 came along and thus it didn't sell and died.  They
even made them for the wintel machines but apparantly those didn't sell
either.  Too bad they didn't advertise them and tell the public how much
better they were.


  I wonder if GI would sell the rights to the design reasonably.  I bet if
I was marketing them they would sell!  I would make sure that the adds
told people very clearly how they were better.


  Dang me, I got carried away again but I HATE seeing good technology
getting beaten out by crap.



cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



