@NODE "Mail_250" "Re: I Hate outlook express (Re: Amiga Release The Technology Brief)"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sun, 18 Jul 1999 19:19:03 +0100
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: I Hate outlook express (Re: Amiga Release The Technology Brief)
X-UIDL: dd202e9d368470438f7143b5fb48126c

I watched as Mikkel Lokke hammered "Re: I Hate outlook express (Re: Amiga
Release The Technology Brief)" out on their keyboard...

>> Yet another full stop on a single line makes me download 20 emails 5
>> times....oh joy ;)..did any one else have this problem with this email??

> I don't get it ? What's the problem ? Another design flaw in a Microsoft
> product ? Say it ain't so ! Tell me more about it, I'm sure it can be
> exploited, I know tons of unsuspecting PC owners that deserve it. :o>

Technically, it shouldn't ever happen.  So it comes as no suprise that
Microsoft managed to fuck up even the simplest of protocols.

SMTP and POP3 rely on the "." to indicate when it hs reached the end of an
e-mail.  For example, when you send an e-mail to an SMTP server, the Syntax
goes something like this:

--
RCPTO rick@whereever.com
DATA
[message goes here]
[more of message etc]
.
--
Then the mailer moves onto the next message, the end of the data section is
indicated by the single "." on a single line (some UNIX programs use this
to tell when you have finished typing etc).

POP3 goes like this:
--
C: USER rick
S: +OK
C: PASS mypassword
S: +OK 3 3230            <- 3 messages totaling 3230 bytes
C: RETR 1                <- Order the server to send us messge id "1"
S: +OK 1420 octets       <- Message is 1420 bytes long
S: [message data]
S: .                     <- Indicates the end of the message
--

Now somehow, when MS Outlook sends E-Mails it is managing to break this and
put a "." on a single line inside an e-mail body.  So when the user comes
to download the message, half way through the software gets a "." from the
server and promptly thinks that that is the end of the message, but of
course it isn't, and so the client goes on and tries to get the next
message, but instead gets what looks like a load of gibberish, but what is
actually the remainder of the previous e-mail.

And so, yet again, MS manages to fuck up a perfectly good, working protocol
in such a way that will cause users all over the globe no end of hassle.

-- 
