@NODE "Mail_262" "Re: Interleaved migranes"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Mon, 5 Jul 1999 11:33:33 +0100
Subject: Re: Interleaved migranes
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 28788d5e801dcc7a70c6718ada377c64

> Look, I figured that I could sort out how to code an interleaved-bitmap,
> but to no avail.  I end up with screwed up pictures and the like.  I've
> been basing my interleaved bitmap routine on making an Interlaced screen
> in Blitz mode.
> 
> If anyone has any source code or a remedy to doing this, it would be much
> appreciated.

I doubt if you'd be able to use the normal routines for blitting or drawing, I 
think they would all assume a non-interleaved bitmap. Dave's CPU blitting 
routines were written for interleaved bitmaps I think, but I don't know where 
to get them from. Manfred Lizner also done CPU blitting routines but I don't 
know if they work with interleaved bitmaps either, you can find them on Ruis 
website (http://www.ip.pt/~ip234558/).

The loadiff command (or whatever one it is to load pictures into bitmaps) may 
or may not work with interleaved bitmaps, I've never tried it.

One thing you will definately have to check for is your coplist must be set up 
so that the bitmaps will be displayed properly. And its more of a pain in the 
arse for interlaced interleaved bitmaps (hey Rob, interlaced was bad enough 
eh?).

I don't have the code on me for setting up a hires-laced coplist, but to get it 
to work for hires-laced-interleaved, you'd need to increase the modulo (the 
number of bytes that the copper skips at the end of each line being displayed) 
so that it would display the right parts of the bitmap. The modulo would end up 
being:

(width of bitmap in bytes) * (depth of bitmap * 2 - 1)

Perhaps.

I'll send you the code later so you'll maybe understand what I'm babbling about.

