@NODE "Mail_279" "Life is GOOD!!!"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Fri, 09 Jul 1999 08:17:17 +0500
Subject: Life is GOOD!!!
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 4717bb7c4a659efb946ee49c3f744d82

On 07-Jul-99, Mikkel Lřkke flashed:
>Hello Tony.

>You wrote:
>> Donovan mentioned, the other day, that the Boxer will remove the 2Mb
>> Chip ram limitation.   Since it will also have a built-in
>> flicker-fixed and scan-doubler, will there be any point in getting a
>> graphics board as well as a boxer?

>You mean appart from being able to display high reslution graphics, in high
or
>true colour, really REALLY fast ? No.


  So far they have speeded up AGA by about 30% and removed the 2mb chip ram
limitation.  If they were to continue to add new capability to their version
of the Amiga chip set by supporting higher screen resolutions and more sound
channels, etc. things could really get interesting.
  I am getting this machine because I want something which will run old Amiga
software (not just AmigaOS 3.5 compliant stuff) and still be upgradeable to
a NG Amiga and run that stuff too.  This is the plan with the Boxer.  Besides,
it will work with existing Zorro slot cards and present Amiga input devices
such as my "I'll kill anyone who tries to take them away from me" Golden
image optical mice which are so superior to any other it's amazing, and
which can't be had on ANY platform (nor anything like them) for any price
any more.  (If anyone is curious why I love them so much, it's because unlike
all other optical mice they work flawlessly and without hassels no matter
which way you hold them, and will even work fairly well on ANY surface which
has any sort of light/dark pattern whether from color or texture.  In short,
they totally fullfill the promise of optical mice to get rid of the problems
of sticky mechanical mecanisms without the tracking problems which plague
most optical mice.  It's to bad everybody didn't discover how good they were
before Golden Image decided there wasn't any market for them and discontinued
them.)
  By the way, does anyone here have any Golden Image OPTICAL mice they want
to sell?

  Back to the Boxer.  The other reasons I am getting one are that for
sentimental and collecting reasons I desire to have one of the last and
greatest of the first family of Amigas, and also, I cant wait another
half year to have a new machine and I'll be hanged if I am going to
waste my money on and be hasseled with the quagmires of wintel machines
or even Macs.  I get WAY to much of those at work, and they are a
continual drain on labor and finances.  Even though the Amiga is not
problem free, it is still the most pleasant platform to use overall.

  I am happy that the plan is to retain this truely user-friendly attitude
in the NG Amigas.  I was NOT looking forward to someday having to choose
one of the other messy platforms if both Amiga as a platform and also
my personal Amigas died.  Fortunatly, now I won't have to make that choice.


  Well sorry for getting so far off topic, peeps...  but I am truely
excited about the developements going on not just with the Amiga hardware
but also with the coming of improvements in user-friendly programming
which is really what this list is all about.  Things like Mildred make
all of our lives both easier and more exciting (thanks, Paul... whereever
you are), and several others here have also been contributing to the
improvement of Blitz.  And I am especially excited about Freds new "Powr
Basic" and looking forward to giving that a whirl.



Ahhhhh...  Life is GOOD!!!



Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



