; RUN THIS FROM THE CLI ONCE COMPILED=00; Run this program before the oth=
er one from the CLI, i.e.=00; 1> run prog_a <RETURN>=00; 1> run prog_b <R=
ETURN>=00=00; You will need blitzlibs:amigalibs.res resident=00; ********=
**************************************=00=00; This program creates a publ=
ic message port (so that other programs can=00; talk to it, this is not r=
equired if the stuff that uses your message=00; port is set up by yoursel=
f, i.e. commodities). It then waits for messages to=00; arrive. Any messa=
ges that arrive get their number changed and returned.=00; Once all messa=
ges are processed, the program ends.=00=80=C3=00=80=0B =B5=03=3D0 =80! =80=
=02=00=00; The message will come in this form=00=80=01.NrMessage=00  Syst=
emMsg.Message=00  number.w=00=80=02 =80=01=00=00; Declare a pointer to ou=
r message port=00=803.MsgPort *msgp=00=00; Declare a pointer to the messa=
ge=00=803.NrMessage *nrmsg=00=00; Start of main program=00; Try to create=
 a message port: Name "NrPort", priority 0=00*msgp =3D =FE=E2=00=80=0B *m=
sgp =3D 0=00  =DD=82 "Could not create message port!"=00  =80=02=00=80=02=
 =80=0B=00myportname$=3D "NrPort" ; NB: This string should not be changed=
, as the pointer=00                      ;     in the message port struct=
ure will point to it!=00*msgp\mp_Node\ln_Pri =3D 0=00*msgp\mp_Node\ln_Nam=
e =3D &myportname$=00=FE=B1 *msgp  ; Add message port to the list of publ=
ic message ports=00=00; Wait for a message to arrive=00=DD=82 "A: Waiting=
 for message to arrive..."=00;WaitPort_ *msgp ; NB: You could alternative=
ly do the following (allows you to=00                ;     wait for >1 me=
ssage port). If using the following,=00                ;     you must com=
pare returnMask to all the other masks you=00                ;     use, t=
o check what has sent you the signal. I added=00                ;     che=
cking for CTRL-C to show what to do!=00msgpMask.l =3D 1 =80| *msgp\mp_Sig=
Bit=00signalset.l =3D msgpMask | #SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C ; Add other signals to=
 this using logical OR=00returnMask.l =3D =FE=AB(signalset)=00=00=80=0B r=
eturnMask =3D msgpMask=00  ; Now one or more messages has arrived, try to=
 collect as many=00  ; messages as possible=00  *nrmsg =3D =FE=B4(*msgp)=00=
  =80=0C (*nrmsg)=00    ; Read the message=00    =DD=82 "A: The value rec=
eived was: ",*nrmsg\number=00=00    ; Alter it=00    *nrmsg\number =3D =BC=
=07(32000)=00    =DD=82 "A: Value changed to: ",*nrmsg\number=00=00    ; =
Reply to message=00    =FE=B5 *nrmsg=00    ; Now that we have replied, we=
 cannot change or access the message any more!=00    *nrmsg =3D =FE=B4(*m=
sgp)=00  =80=C1=00=80=02 =80=0B=00=00=80=0B returnMask =3D #SIGBREAKF_CTR=
L_C =80! =DD=82 "You pressed CTRL-C!"=00=00; Start clean up, use this nex=
t loop to clear port of all messages before=00; removing it from public l=
ist, then deleting=00*nrmsg =3D =FE=B4(*msgp)=00=80=0C (*nrmsg)=00  =FE=B5=
 *nrmsg=00  *nrmsg =3D =FE=B4(*msgp)=00=80=C1=00=FE=B2 *msgp          ; r=
emove port from list of public ports=00=FE=E3 *msgp    ; delete message p=
ort=00=DD=82 "The end!"=00=80=02=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=00=
