@NODE "Mail_318" "Re: Multiplayer game tests!"
From: Stephen Lebed <slebed@earthlink.net>
Date: Sun, 18 Jul 1999 13:01:22 -0800
Subject: Re: Multiplayer game tests!
X-UIDL: 77d3f51f8a99aa0c1578527402817ad1

Hi there Anton

On 17-Jul-99, you wrote:

>  Me and Chris Deeney did some testing on Sat night, with his
> multiplayer game (called Lifter at the moment), which uses my UDP
> functions for the multiplayer internet link. His game is only in a
> basic state at the moment- just flying around, so I don't think you'll
> get a demo just yet :-)  Even so, we had great fun!!!
> 
>  Well, it all seemed to run fine, apart from some small glitches, so
> having a game with a Net connection and Chunky graphics on AGA is
> feasible on a 68k! :-))))
> 
>   On my 25/040 there was no difference in framerate than there was
> without the net connection, but on Chris's 50/030, there was a bit of a
> slowdown. With Vwait off (the display still looks fine BTW), it was
> running at 25 fps very smoothly on the 040 :-) 
>  I'll have to optimise my funcs- get rid of the string manipulation,
> and replace it with assem (which I intended to do anyway), so it will
> work better on 030s. Note: that some of that CPU time is due to Miami,
> so that can't be changed.  
>  Also, I could still do stuff in the background even with the Vwait
> off- it was slow, but Dopus, IRC etc worked ok. With VWait on it used
> 78% CPU, and off it used 100%.
> 
>  Just thought you all would be interested :-)

Congrats on your experiment.  I'm looking forward to further updates of UDP.
 I'm laying down the framework for a test tank game to be played over the
internet.  I'd like to know what type of connection you guys were on, and
how you managed syncing your frames together?  Also, was your UDP packets
sent at timed intervals?   How was the latency, any problems?

Sorry for all the questions...

Stephen Lebed
slebed@earthlink.net


