@NODE "Mail_323" "Re: New P5/QNX machine!!"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Mon, 26 Jul 1999 06:18:36 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: New P5/QNX machine!!
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 1dd158300e88fd5b30620d953bb7cc38

Hello Anton.

You wrote:
> And this is a very interesting article by Wolf Dietrich on the current
> Amiga situation - very important for programmers- I have to say I was
> thinking along the same lines even before I read it!

Blah, blah blah. Won't you guys ever shut up (Not specifically you anton, but everyone who sees action by AMiGA as some bad thing) ? No-one knows what AMiGA is planning, so how can you judge them ? Wolf says it himself "We don't know what AMiGA is doing", well, how can he know it's bad ?

He then goes on to tell how you for a small fortune can get your AMiGA (Classic I take it) beefed up to the level of modern computers, and tells everyone that the MCC doesn't have much in common with the old AMiGA's (which he doesn't know for a fact). Well, IMHO a PPC AMiGA (PCC originally design for Macs) with a CVPCC (Permedia 2 originally designed for PC's) doesn't have much in common with AMiGA classics either.

He then goes on to tell how inovative they're gonna be by following the mainstream. (For christs sake, am I the only one who's starting too see something wrong with this picture ?)

He than starts describing how "unfair" it is that AMiGA is joining a partnership with Corel, and blames AMiGA for choosing things that are popular. (A smart move IMHO) The fact of the matter (Whether Wold Dietrich likes it or not) things that are popular have huge sales, so developing for things that are popular will bring in more money. Imagine if sadeness had been able to sell Foundation from the shops, I know at least two people who would have been happy. (Me, since I would have had a descent chance of buying the game, and Paul Burkey, becasue he would probably have made 20 times more money.)

Oh, one other thing, Wolf bashes AMiGA for not letting developers in on the secrets, he then says something like "Why don't AMiGA anounce that ImageFX is shiping with the AMiGANG ?" Well I spoke to Kermit Woodall of Nova Design at WOA, and he was looking forward to the MCC. So I guess Wolf hasn't even got his facts straight, what a high level of professionalism, I wonder if that's why AMiGA didn't tell Phase 5 anything.

I didn't even read the last half of the letter, because it's really late (or early) and I was falling asleep.

The last note on this matter Phase five have promised new and revolutionary "Next Generation AMiGA's" before (This is revolutionary AMiGA #4 to my counting) I mean honestly ? How stupid do they think we are ? Also Wolf's letter clearly indicates that I am better informed about what happens on the AMiGA front, (which is really sad, coz no-one tells me anything) He indicates that the next generation is gonna be Java and Linux ? Well, either he understands Operating systems and programming worse than I (Which is no small feat), og he's just plain stupid.

Oh, and you can tie me to the tail pipe of your car and drag me accross a field of broken glass NAKED at 50 MPH, I would NEVER use a Macintosh E-mail client. Especially not while I'm telling everyone how much I love the AMiGA...

Oh, and Anton, once again, this is not an attack on you or your oppinion, I'm just sick and tired of people whinning who AMiGA are "abandoning the AMiGA Classic". Well of course they are ! It's ancient ! 32-bit motherboard, 16Megs of RAM, 2 megs of chip. If it wheren't so damned tragic, it would be a bloody joke. I for one would rather have the AMiGA BACK on the shelves, than lets P5 turn it into an ATARI. (Oh yes, they're still arround, they have multiple 060's and PPC's (And they run Linux too BTW :o> Ecept they use the whole bloody thing, not just the kernel) and you're never gonna GUESS the price tag)...

Sorry again Anton... I'm getting abit carried away, I'll just shut up now, before I start off again.


Greets,
-- 

.---+----- --- -- -  -   -    -     -      -      -
-----------  / /__ ----------- http://www.m2p.dk --
            /_____| Productions/

