@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_324" "Re: New P5/QNX machine!!"
Date: Mon, 26 Jul 1999 13:00:24 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: New P5/QNX machine!!
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 6eedd6e435fe1391c15d7f0c4ac42061

Mikkel Lřkke wrote:
> Blah, blah blah. Won't you guys ever shut up (Not specifically you
> anton, but everyone who sees action by AMiGA as some bad thing) ?
> No-one knows what AMiGA is planning, so how can you judge them ?
> Wolf says it himself "We don't know what AMiGA is doing", well, how
> can he know it's bad ?

He probably does know what Amiga are doing. I was at WoA and managed
to speak to many people from Amiga Journalists to Amiga software
publishers/retailers. All of these people did know what Amiga
are up to and the WoA itself was the place where subtle hints went
a little too far because nobody can keep the secret much longer.
Since the WoA I have been reading as many facts as I can about the
Transmeta chip in order to work out why people are getting so
excited!

As I said, Phase 5 know what Amiga have planned and there doesn't seem
to be any room for them in the scheme of things. Amiga MCC wont
need Accelerators or GFX cards for quite some time. Perhaps Phase 5
will be in the 'Amiga Clone' industry as soon as it suits them.

> He then goes on to tell how you for a small fortune can get your
> AMiGA (Classic I take it) beefed up to the level of modern
> computers, and tells everyone that the MCC doesn't have much in
> common with the old AMiGA's (which he doesn't know for a fact).

The MCC has a lot in common with Classic Amiga. If Amiga first
appeared in 1999 then it would look much like the MCC :) It's a
shame we didn't see the Amiga evolve into the MCC through a smooth
gradual path, but revolutions don't work that way.

> He than starts describing how "unfair" it is that AMiGA is
> joining a partnership with Corel, and blames AMiGA for choosing
> things that are popular. (A smart move IMHO)

As more information about MCC appears, everything falls into place.
The choice of CPU, the Kernel, working with Linus on the OE, Corel,
Adobe, Sun, Transmeta etc. It's all great stuff when you see the
full picture.

> Imagine if sadeness had been able to sell Foundation from the
> shops, I know at least two people who would have been happy.
> (Me, since I would have had a descent chance of buying the game,
> and Paul Burkey, becasue he would probably have made 20 times
> more money.)

Sadeness were yet another victim of a tough market which rarely gives
people what they deserve. One retailer I spoke to at WoA told me
how he is forced to sell titles that were "appalling quality" but
keeping a wide spectrum of software titles for all tastes is the
only way these people can survive. Sadeness decided to publish only
the titles they liked and it didn't work out.

The WoA was great! Especially the after show Banquet and free booze. I
discovered enough about Amiga MCC to fuel a new Foundation release
with a new publisher for a new Amiga! 



-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


