@NODE "Mail_325" "Re: New P5/QNX machine!!rt,"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Mon, 26 Jul 1999 08:20:36 +0500
Subject: Re: New P5/QNX machine!!rt,
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 6825f9e4a7058b23240b17eaee32f991

On 26-Jul-99, Mikkel Lřkke flashed:

-clip-

>everyone who sees action by AMiGA as some bad thing) ? No-one knows what
AMiGA
>is planning, so how can you judge them ? Wolf says it himself "We don't know
>what AMiGA is doing", well, how can he know it's bad ?

  True.  Besides, what Amiga have outlined so far sounds quite good to me.

>He then goes on to tell how you for a small fortune can get your AMiGA
>(Classic I take it) beefed up to the level of modern computers, and tells
>everyone that the MCC doesn't have much in common with the old AMiGA's (which
>he doesn't know for a fact). Well, IMHO a PPC AMiGA (PCC originally design
for
>Macs) with a CVPCC (Permedia 2 originally designed for PC's) doesn't have
much
>in common with AMiGA classics either.

  Precisely.  We have been griping for years about how the old Amigas were
being allowed to stagnate and get out of date, and how we didn't want just
a improved rehash but we wanted something really cool, and something that
could use all the commonly available cheap add-ons.  Well, now that Amiga
are trying to give us basically just what we asked for, I think it's a
little silly of us to continue treating them like the enemy.
  I personally don't want anything that's stuck in any of the old ruts,
just something that's friendly and effecient like the old Amigas.
What Mr. Dietrich has outlined (multiple EXPENSIVE processors and totally
propriatory design) sounds more like EXPENSIVE and INEFFICIENT to me.
  Frankly, I don't think I could afford to buy Phase5's new dream machine.
I can't really even afford thier accelerator cards (which cost as much or
more than a NEW Amiga is going to if the Amiga cost estimates turn out to
be in the ballpark).
  And Mr. Dietrich talks about abandonment... pshawww.  Phase5 are FAMOUS
for that.  They jump from one thing to the next without a thought, leaving
a trail of abandoned customers in their wake.  I bought a Cybervision3D
when they were saying how great it was and how they were going to make all
these cool add-ons for it, only to be jolted to reality but a few months
later when they dropped all developement for it and announced that they
were not supporting it any further.  If I wanted any of the cool add-ons
they were talking about I would have to buy one of their accelerator cards
and a whole new graphics card to fit it, and THEN I could get the cool
add-ons.  Yeah, right.  Where are they all?  Now they are jumping off on
yet another unrealistic and unsubstantiated tangent and -mark my words-
all the announced cool add-ons for their accelerators will never appear.
First they try to force everyone to buy only their products by making the
firmware reject other systems, then they don't support their products
themselves, leaving their customers stuck.  Very microsoft like.
  I very much respect the Phase5 teams abilities in hardware design and
I have no doubt thet if they actually come up with a computer it will
be technically cool.  Unfortunatly, it will also be based on yesterdays
(expensive) processor which only has a few years life left in it.
  I would be very interested to see what (if anything) Phase5 come up
with, but it's highly unlikely I would buy one (much like the Drako).



>He then goes on to tell how inovative they're gonna be by following the
>mainstream. (For christs sake, am I the only one who's starting too see
>something wrong with this picture ?)


  Nope.  It looks pretty slanty to me too.



>He than starts describing how "unfair" it is that AMiGA is joining a
>partnership with Corel, and blames AMiGA for choosing things that are
popular.
>(A smart move IMHO) The fact of the matter (Whether Wold Dietrich likes it or
>not) things that are popular have huge sales, so developing for things that
>are popular will bring in more money. Imagine if sadeness had been able to
>sell Foundation from the shops, I know at least two people who would have
been
>happy. (Me, since I would have had a descent chance of 
>buying the game, and Paul Burkey, becasue he would probably have made 20
times
>more money.)


  Yep.  I think Amiga are doing quite a good job of choosing a path which will
give the advantages of mainstream third party products without losing the new
power, freedom, versitility and innovation we all want.



>Oh, one other thing, Wolf bashes AMiGA for not letting developers in on the
>secrets, he then says something like "Why don't AMiGA anounce that ImageFX is
>shiping with the AMiGANG ?" Well I spoke to Kermit Woodall of Nova Design at
>WOA, and he was looking forward to the MCC. So I guess Wolf hasn't even got
>his facts straight, what a high level of professionalism, I wonder if that's
>why AMiGA didn't tell Phase 5 anything.


  Right on the nose.  You guessed it.  Amiga don't trust P5 because of their
tendacy to do just such things as this.



>I didn't even read the last half of the letter, because it's really late (or
>early) and I was falling asleep.


  I read it all, and it was more of the same as you no doubt guessed.


>The last note on this matter Phase five have promised new and revolutionary
>"Next Generation AMiGA's" before (This is revolutionary AMiGA #4 to my
>counting) I mean honestly ? How stupid do they think we are ? Also Wolf's
>letter clearly indicates that I am better informed about what happens on the
>AMiGA front, (which is really sad, coz no-one tells me anything) He indicates
>that the next generation is gonna be Java and Linux ? Well, either he
>understands Operating systems and programming worse than I (Which
> is no small feat), og he's just plain stupid.


  He isn't stupid.  He just doesn't want Amiga to succeed.  He wants P5 to
take Amigas place, despite all his words to the contrary.  From his viewpoint,
i can't blame him for wanting to have his business grow and even dominate,
but it wouldn't be to the benefit of the Amigan such as ourselves.


>Oh, and you can tie me to the tail pipe of your car and drag me accross a
>field of broken glass NAKED at 50 MPH, I would NEVER use a Macintosh E-mail
>client. Especially not while I'm telling everyone how much I love the
AMiGA...

>Oh, and Anton, once again, this is not an attack on you or your oppinion, I'm
>just sick and tired of people whinning who AMiGA are "abandoning the AMiGA
>Classic". Well of course they are ! It's ancient ! 32-bit motherboard, 16Megs
>of RAM, 2 megs of chip. If it wheren't so damned tragic, it would be a bloody
>joke. I for one would rather have the AMiGA BACK on the shelves, than lets P5
>turn it into an ATARI. (Oh yes, they're still arround, they have multiple
>060's and PPC's (And they run Linux too BTW :o> Ec
>ept they use the whole bloody thing, not just the kernel) and you're never
>gonna GUESS the price tag)...


  Yup.  Let's move on.  After all, Amiga are providing the best possible
solutions for those (like myself) who wish to keep using some older
software...
they are giving us an improved legacy O.S. with possibility of even further
improvements in the future, and BEST OF ALL they are providing FULL HARDWARE
SUPPORTED EMULATION for legacy software in the new Amigas.  They are not
abandoning the old Amigas at all.  They are in fact doing everything possible
(short of screwing up the new machines) to support and ease the transition,
and even to support those who may want to continue to run older Amigas
indefinately.  We get to have our cake and eat it too!!!
  I personally am making a collection of Legacy Amigas, just for fun.  We have
fun using them too, playing some of the old classic games from time to time.
  Besides, I believe that Amigas will in the future become by far the most
collectable of all computers, having been a breakthrough design which made
history, but yet being relatively rare.

  The new Amigas will not be anything like the old ones physically, but they
WILL carry forward the Grand Amiga Tradition.  Amigas have always been
sweet, intelligent, capable,imaginative, slim, trim and sexy.  The new
generation of Amigas will also have these attributes.


>Sorry again Anton... I'm getting abit carried away, I'll just shut up now,
>before I start off again.


  I am sure Anton realises that you weren't attacking him.

  I don't blame Anton for getting excited about this developement.
It is very significant, though it may mean trouble.  The plans of
Amiga will actually make it easier for other companys to start new
platforms because they will weaken the wintel monopoly.  I actually hope
Phase5 achieve something, and I wish them well, but it appears to me
that they are leaving the Amiga arena.  Of course, they are to a large
extent a Mac company allready, which is why they are so stuck on PPC.

  Don't get me wrong, PPC is a good processor, much better than pentium,
and I intend to use them in several of my Legacy Amigas.  For now, they
are the best way to go until the new Amigas are ready.  But that doesn't
change tha fact that they are yesterdays design.  Even Motorola is busy
prepareing a replacement for them.


  Well, I too have said enough.  Chins up!  We actually CAN have a
revolution if we allow it.  The revolution is not any one part of the
picture, but the whole taken together, including the Amiga tradition
and the Amiga community, US.  In the future, stuff like we have been
involved in here with Blitz will be GREAT FUN because of all the POWER
and VERSITILITY we will have at our command.  And thanks to innovators
like Fred, Paul, Dave, David, Anton, Curt, Rob, Mikkel, Danial, Rick, James,
Sami, Jeroen, Damir, Gareth, Toby, Vic, Stephen, Lee, Leigh, Neil, Ian,
Ayar, Roger, Bippy, Mathias, Ashley, Andrew, Anthony, Bernard, Lance, Opi,
Chris, Wremu, Jake, Julian, Jonas, Simon, Tony, Anthony, Liz, our dearly
departed other Paul, and everyone else on this list whose names escape
me now,  we will continue to enjoy the Amiga experience.



cach y'all later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



