  The main reason I liked the the sound of a P5 machine, was AI's use of
Linux and Sun's Java. Now AI say that the memory use of the Linux
kernal, has been brought to an `acceptable' amount- hmmm, what does
`acceptable' mean- by Amiga or Windows standards? QNX we know uses only
a small amount of resources.
   That aside, the main thing that worries me, is that Sun's Java is
horribly inefficient, as it uses a large amount of memory, and CPU
time- the free Linux version of Java (forgotten the name now :/ , doing
the same code, on the same machine, ran about 3-5 times faster than the
Sun version! If Sun's Java is powering the upper OS, it's not gonna be
a small tight OS- and as for using it in imbedded devices- Ha! How is
it going to be much better than Windows CE?
   If we can program in Basic/C/assem and access those Java classes-
then it maybe alright.
  
>> He then goes on to tell how you for a small fortune can get your
>> AMiGA (Classic I take it) beefed up to the level of modern computers,
>> and tells everyone that the MCC doesn't have much in common with the
>> old AMiGA's (which he doesn't know for a fact). Well, IMHO a PPC
>> AMiGA (PCC originally design
> for
>> Macs) with a CVPCC (Permedia 2 originally designed for PC's) doesn't
>> have
> much
>> in common with AMiGA classics either.

>  Precisely. We have been griping for years about how the old Amigas
> were being allowed to stagnate and get out of date, and how we didn't
> want just a improved rehash but we wanted something really cool, and
> something that could use all the commonly available cheap add-ons.
> Well, now that Amiga are trying to give us basically just what we
> asked for, I think it's a little silly of us to continue treating them
> like the enemy.
>  I personally don't want anything that's stuck in any of the old
> ruts, just something that's friendly and effecient like the old
> Amigas.

  Well, a 1200 with a PPC board is not what an AMIRAGE will be, it's
hardware specs sounds similar to AI's machine, but should run more
efficiently, as it uses QNX, not JAVA.  
  Actually for those of us already with a PPC board, all you need is
a BVision card and SVGA monitor, to allow you to program for the new OS-
much cheaper than a new machine! It would give me time to save up for a
new machine, as programming on Amigas hasn't made anyone rich in the
past few years! :-)

> What Mr. Dietrich has outlined (multiple EXPENSIVE processors
> and totally propriatory design) sounds more like EXPENSIVE and
> INEFFICIENT to me.

  Multiple processors, are only an option, the majority of uses would
only get a machine with one CPU- the multiple CPU thing is there for
power users, and a *cheap* upgrade path- in a year or so, just chuck in
another CPU.

>  Frankly, I don't think I could afford to buy Phase5's new dream
> machine. I can't really even afford thier accelerator cards (which
> cost as much or more than a NEW Amiga is going to if the Amiga cost
> estimates turn out to be in the ballpark).

 Yes, of course they were, as the amount of boards they could sell was
very limited- they had to keep their heads above water financially! A
new machine could sell a large amount (if it took off of course), so
would be cheaper.

>  And Mr. Dietrich talks about abandonment... pshawww. Phase5 are
> FAMOUS for that. They jump from one thing to the next without a
> thought, leaving a trail of abandoned customers in their wake. I
> bought a Cybervision3D when they were saying how great it was and how
> they were going to make all these cool add-ons for it, only to be
> jolted to reality but a few months later when they dropped all
> developement for it and announced that they were not supporting it any
> further. If I wanted any of the cool add-ons they were talking about I
> would have to buy one of their accelerator cards and a whole new
> graphics card to fit it, and THEN I could get the cool add-ons. Yeah,
> right. Where are they all? Now they are jumping off on yet another
> unrealistic and unsubstantiated tangent and -mark my words- all the
> announced cool add-ons for their accelerators will never appear. First
> they try to force everyone to buy only their products by making the
> firmware reject other systems, then they don't support their products
> themselves, leaving their customers stuck. Very microsoft like.
>  I very much respect the Phase5 teams abilities in hardware design
> and I have no doubt thet if they actually come up with a computer it
> will be technically cool.

  Yeah, they've done some fucked things I totally agree, but then again,
they were doing major hardware development on bugger all money, without
even knowing if they'd go under in the process- the whole time they
seemed to be `only just hanging in there'. Like they only had one
person writing the PPC lib, and the website always seemed to be updated
`if they had the time' :-/ 

> Unfortunatly, it will also be based on
> yesterdays (expensive) processor which only has a few years life left
> in it.

  I don't know about that, the G4 with the Altivec and copper
technology, looks very nice!  We don't even know what CPU the MMC will
run on yet! It sounds like it will be the MIPS, I haven't researched it
up yet, does anyone know what it's like? 

>> He then goes on to tell how inovative they're gonna be by following
>> the mainstream. (For christs sake, am I the only one who's starting
>> too see something wrong with this picture ?)

>  Nope.  It looks pretty slanty to me too.

  Um, didn't he say that about AI?

>> He than starts describing how "unfair" it is that AMiGA is joining a
>> partnership with Corel, and blames AMiGA for choosing things that are
> popular.
>> (A smart move IMHO) The fact of the matter (Whether Wold Dietrich
>> likes it or not) things that are popular have huge sales, so
>> developing for things that are popular will bring in more money.
>> Imagine if sadeness had been able to sell Foundation from the shops,
>> I know at least two people who would have
> been
>> happy. (Me, since I would have had a descent chance of buying the
