> times
>> more money.)

>  Yep. I think Amiga are doing quite a good job of choosing a path
> which will give the advantages of mainstream third party products
> without losing the new power, freedom, versitility and innovation we
> all want.

  Yes, the main thing about the AI comments that I wondered about, was
the oh, we need all the Linux software, to be up to date, we couldn't
get that on QNX- and I thought, what about the Amiga developers?
They've kept the Amiga up-to-date so far (even a lot for the PPC CPU),
and that's without getting paid (or very little)- then what could they
do if AI decided to pay them!! This was the main thing in Wolf's
comments that I agreed with. I agree there was a lot of scare-mongering
in it as well, but that was the most annoying thing of the Linux
announcement- oh and using X-Windows sounds dicey as well.

>> Oh, one other thing, Wolf bashes AMiGA for not letting developers in
>> on the secrets, he then says something like "Why don't AMiGA anounce
>> that ImageFX is shiping with the AMiGANG ?" Well I spoke to Kermit
>> Woodall of Nova Design at WOA, and he was looking forward to the MCC.
>> So I guess Wolf hasn't even got his facts straight, what a high level
>> of professionalism, I wonder if that's why AMiGA didn't tell Phase 5
>> anything.

>  Right on the nose. You guessed it. Amiga don't trust P5 because of
> their tendacy to do just such things as this.

>> The last note on this matter Phase five have promised new and
>> revolutionary "Next Generation AMiGA's" before (This is revolutionary
>> AMiGA #4 to my counting) I mean honestly ? How stupid do they think
>> we are ?

   Come on- on what budget? What with the earlier Amiga annoucements of
a new Amiga it would have been financial suicide.

> Also Wolf's letter clearly indicates that I am better
>> informed about what happens on the AMiGA front, (which is really sad,
>> coz no-one tells me anything) He indicates that the next generation
>> is gonna be Java and Linux ? Well, either he understands Operating
>> systems and programming worse than I (Which
>> is no small feat), og he's just plain stupid.

   No-one really knows what the OS is yet (unless you're under an NDA),
as AI has been rather airy-fairy so far on the OS side of things. 

>  He isn't stupid. He just doesn't want Amiga to succeed. He wants P5
> to take Amigas place, despite all his words to the contrary. From his
> viewpoint, i can't blame him for wanting to have his business grow and
> even dominate, but it wouldn't be to the benefit of the Amigan such as
> ourselves.

