@NODE "Mail_327" "Re: New P5/QNX machine!!rt,"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 27 Jul 1999 06:07:53 -0500
Subject: Re: New P5/QNX machine!!rt,
X-UIDL: 3b365a6516a7b6c3f78cc0afab4f39f3

Hi Everybody,

I've tried to keep my virtual mouth shut on this subject, but I just had to
throw in a few comments.  

>>> everyone who sees action by AMiGA as some bad thing) ? No-one knows
>>> what
>> AMiGA
>>> is planning, so how can you judge them ? Wolf says it himself "We
>>> don't know what AMiGA is doing", well, how can he know it's bad ?

^^^^ that's why I've kept silent - we really DON'T know exactly what AI is
going to come up with, or for that matter P5...

>  The main reason I liked the the sound of a P5 machine, was AI's use of
> Linux and Sun's Java. Now AI say that the memory use of the Linux
> kernal, has been brought to an `acceptable' amount- hmmm, what does
> `acceptable' mean- by Amiga or Windows standards? QNX we know uses only
> a small amount of resources.

^^^^ I think this brings up the key point I want to make.  It seems
everybody is forgetting that this is going to be a NEW machine - not an
A5000 or something...

Thinking of it in terms of the current Amiga is like comparing the A500 to
the C64.

The current Amiga OS is very efficient, in terms of what it is capable of. 
But compared to the C64's OS it is a bloated monster - remember the C64
could run the entire OS as well as a program in only 64k of memory, with
room to spare  :)

>   That aside, the main thing that worries me, is that Sun's Java is
> horribly inefficient, as it uses a large amount of memory, and CPU
> time- the free Linux version of Java (forgotten the name now :/ , doing
> the same code, on the same machine, ran about 3-5 times faster than the
> Sun version! If Sun's Java is powering the upper OS, it's not gonna be
> a small tight OS- and as for using it in imbedded devices- Ha! How is
> it going to be much better than Windows CE?
>   If we can program in Basic/C/assem and access those Java classes-
> then it maybe alright.

Yes, good point.  But I think maybe the Java part will be used in the same
way as Arexx is used now - as communication between programs, not as the
only available programming language.

>>  Precisely. We have been griping for years about how the old Amigas
>> were being allowed to stagnate and get out of date, and how we didn't
>> want just a improved rehash but we wanted something really cool, and
>> something that could use all the commonly available cheap add-ons.
>> Well, now that Amiga are trying to give us basically just what we
>> asked for, I think it's a little silly of us to continue treating them
>> like the enemy.
>>  I personally don't want anything that's stuck in any of the old
>> ruts, just something that's friendly and effecient like the old
>> Amigas.

Exactly!  Or rather, from a user's point of view  (something that we as
programmers sometimes forget?):

I really don't mind if it is somewhat inefficient, if this provides for
future expanision and non-obsolescense.

As a user, I want a machine that's fast and responsive, easy to operate,
does what I want it to, doesn't crash or give me other problems, and can
access the inexpensive hardware I see in the PC shops.

What I DON'T want is to have to upgrade my processor/memory every few
months, take the damn thing into a shop to add new hardware, dig through
manuals or call jammed help lines every time I want to do something
different - in other words, I want to avoid what I call the "PC ratrace". 

>>> He than starts describing how "unfair" it is that AMiGA is joining a
>>> partnership with Corel, and blames AMiGA for choosing things that are
>> popular.
>>> (A smart move IMHO) The fact of the matter (Whether Wold Dietrich
>>> likes it or not) things that are popular have huge sales, so
>>> developing for things that are popular will bring in more money.

>>  Yep. I think Amiga are doing quite a good job of choosing a path
>> which will give the advantages of mainstream third party products
>> without losing the new power, freedom, versitility and innovation we
>> all want.

Again, I agree.  I don't want to see the new Amiga wind up hidden in the
shadows again...
> It's interesting to hear other developers views, as what
> we chose will have a massive effect on these machines- and the last
> thing we want is to split the Amiga community! Also, it's rather hard
> to get the true picture at the moment, so any comments are welcome!

Well, you've got mine  ;)

>   I actually like the sound the AI hardware (although don't know
> anything about the new CPU yet), it's wether the kernal/OS will be
> efficient is what bothers me- I couldn't stand programming on something
> inefficient- as a programmer it goes against the grain! :-)

Agreed.  But it's up to us to make it efficient I think.  See my comment
about the Amiga/C64 above.

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



