That one processor is still expensive, and every penny counts these days.

<Snip>

>> Unfortunatly, it will also be based on
>> yesterdays (expensive) processor which only has a few years life left
>> in it.
> 
>  I don't know about that, the G4 with the Altivec and copper
> technology, looks very nice!  We don't even know what CPU the MMC will
> run on yet! It sounds like it will be the MIPS, I haven't researched it
> up yet, does anyone know what it's like? 

Everyone I know seems to believe that MCC will be powered by Transmeta-
especially after some big time hints at WOA- this chip is looking far nicer
(and apparently cheaper) than the G4.
It's also a lot better at emulation, and is bound to be optimised for the
Linux kernal, with a certain Mr. Torvalds working for them.

>>> He then goes on to tell how inovative they're gonna be by following
>>> the mainstream. (For christs sake, am I the only one who's starting
>>> too see something wrong with this picture ?)
> 
>>  Nope.  It looks pretty slanty to me too.
> 
>  Um, didn't he say that about AI?

Amiga are going to be revolutionary- this convergence stuff is what its all
about, not the fact that they'll be making use of USB etc. The original
Amiga tied things together in a revolutionary way, chucking in some new
odds and ends. (68000s weren't custom built for it, neither were parallel/
serial ports). This new P5 machine though; what's so good about it? It will
run a decent OS (the saving grace) on G4 processors, making use of industry
standard parts. And there isn't nearly the same emphasis on digital
convergence.

<Snip>

>>  He isn't stupid. He just doesn't want Amiga to succeed. He wants P5
>> to take Amigas place, despite all his words to the contrary. From his
>> viewpoint, i can't blame him for wanting to have his business grow and
>> even dominate, but it wouldn't be to the benefit of the Amigan such as
