>On 27-Jul-99, Curt Esser wrote:

>> ^^^^ I think this brings up the key point I want to make. It seems
>> everybody is forgetting that this is going to be a NEW machine - not
>> an A5000 or something...

>> Thinking of it in terms of the current Amiga is like comparing the
>> A500 to the C64.

>> The current Amiga OS is very efficient, in terms of what it is capable
>> of. But compared to the C64's OS it is a bloated monster - remember
>> the C64 could run the entire OS as well as a program in only 64k of
>> memory, with room to spare :)

>   Well, my point was more, wether there would be a significant
>difference between the QNX or the Linux/Java OS solution, in terms of
>memory/CPU usage. I realise there's no way you'll get the entire OS on
>a 720k floppy, if you want standard Java support, networking, DVD etc
>:-)
> 
>>>  That aside, the main thing that worries me, is that Sun's Java is
>>> horribly inefficient, as it uses a large amount of memory, and CPU
>>> time- the free Linux version of Java (forgotten the name now :/ ,
>>> doing the same code, on the same machine, ran about 3-5 times faster
>>> than the Sun version! If Sun's Java is powering the upper OS, it's
>>> not gonna be a small tight OS- and as for using it in imbedded
>>> devices- Ha! How is it going to be much better than Windows CE?
>>>  If we can program in Basic/C/assem and access those Java classes-
>>> then it maybe alright.

>> Yes, good point. But I think maybe the Java part will be used in the
>> same way as Arexx is used now - as communication between programs, not
>> as the only available programming language.

>  Yes, that what I'm hoping for :) Otherwise you couldn't even use Basic
>or assem language! 


  Don't forget that the main OS/OE language for the new Amigas is going to
be C++.  The main OS language for the present Amigas is C also so we will
be still on familiar ground there.  And the whole OE is designed to be open
so as to make it as accessable as possible.  This will cure some of our old
gripes about not being able to access and control some areas of the system.
Even the kernal being in Linux makes it automatically accessable.  A person
will want to be careful to stay within the rules to keep compatability up
though.  But as far as being able to find out how things are configured so
as to use all parts of the system, it should be much easier to get the
needed information.
  As Curt suggested, the Java and Jeni are to be used mainly for interfacing
(like Arexx).  We will have the ability to use the following languages out-
of-the-box:  C++, Java, Jeni, plus through the built-in Amiga legacy support
all languages used on present Amigas.  I suspect there will soon be support
for literally EVERYTHING else because hardware accelerated emulation of
both intel-based machines and Macs is a shoe-in what with the superb
emulation capabilities of the new Amigas, and emulators for everything else
under the sun will no doubt follow (and/or could be used under one of the
other emulations).  ;)
 After, over and above that will come any NEW languages which any whiz kids,
hot rodders, imagenative geniuses and unscrupulous modifiers such as the
here present company of varigated free-thinkers represents will take it
upon themselves to make.

  I'm getting excited just thinking about the possibilities!!!



cach y'all later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



