@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_355" "Re: Performance issues"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Wed, 28 Jul 1999 10:20:31 +0100
Subject: Re: Performance issues
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 3724f201bea4719b55436f896b7c63bb



> In terms of execution speed, is there any difference between

Ah, looks like its come to the desparate stage of trying to make program logic 
quicker ;)

> 1.  MyThing\a = 0,0,0
> 
> and 2.   MyThing\a=o
>             MyThing\b=0
>             MyThing\c=0

The first one may be quicker, it depends on how Blitz compiles it. i.e. the 
second one, each variable may be done by getting the address of thing and then 
setting the appropriate offset to 0 (so it would be done 3 times). The first 
one may only get the address of mything once and then set all the offsets. So 
in this case, assuming it works like that, you'd save a whole 2 instructions.

> Or how about
> If a = b then c = d
> versus
> if a = b
>    c = d
> endif

I'd heard someone say before that the second version is quicker, but I'm sure 
it would compile to the same code.

> or is there any advantage to
> a=b:c=d:e=f
> against
> a=b
> c=d
> e=f

No, they are both the same. Colons just allow you to put multiple lines of code 
onto one line, if you like coding like Mr Sibly (whose ASM is a real pain in 
the arse to read). I think the advantage lies with the second version, as its 
easier to read.

> and finally is there any advantage to doing a UsePath rather than
> spelling it out in full?

Not much. UsePath is a compiler directive, which means its an instruction for 
the compiler, and it expands the \blah at compile time to be a\blah. If you 
have really long variable names, it may help you keep them on one line.


-- 
