@NODE "Mail_360" "Plotting"
From: "Sasu Lintula" <samali@utu.fi>
Subject: Plotting
Date: 	Tue, 20 Jul 1999 23:13:45 +0300
X-UIDL: e28d48511d160da29be4debf57f5adfb



Hi all,
a while ago someone asked if there's any faster way to plot pixels than
blitzs plot -command. I'm not sure if this helps any way but couple years
ago while playing with interleaved bitmaps I discovered that it's possible
use blitter to plot all needed pixels at the same time. It's simple: just
set up blitters line mode (normal modulo) with texture as the needed colour
and draw eight pixels (when using 8 bps) long vertical line - vóila, you got
a single pixel on screen. At that time I noticed this I used a 'simpeline'
routine from hardware ref. manual and am*s (4bps). When compiled routine was
faster than am*s' own plot -routine!
I think this kind of routine could kick ass when using optimized blitter
draw routine (no minterm testing, lenght as constant, etc.). If you store
all colours to word sized tables (f.ex. %10101010 to %1010101010101010) you
can draw multiple pixels at the time just changing the length of line which
is important in scale-routines.
This thing has troubled me a long time - I think it has got potential but I
can't write ASM. Any ASM-God free for try?

[Sasu]



