@NODE "Mail_364" "Vs: Plotting"
From: "Sasu Lintula" <samali@utu.fi>
Subject: Vs: Plotting
Date: 	Mon, 26 Jul 1999 11:27:34 +0300
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8BIT
X-UIDL: f20408dd552c0eb0ebb61153273406a2

Hi Anton and all,

>Yes, we've already got this working onthe List. I can send you the
>examples if you want. :-)
>
>-- 
>        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
   
Yes yes, you sent a source to open an interleaved screen. That's not what I was looking after (althoug nice piece of code).  I wanted to know if there's someone who could write a special optimized blitter line drawing routine for il-screen. This is causing me sleepless nights 'cause I think that kind of routine has a potential so please let me explain:
As far as I know if you are using a some kind of c2p routine and want to draw even only one pixel on screen you have to do that using chunky-buffer (byte->buffer->|c2p|->bitplanes). Now with blitter you just have to set up blitter with proper texture and blit a vertical line. I don't get it why this shouldn't be faster than all kind of c2p conversions. Ok, c2p is handy if you have to update a whole screen at the same time but are you really doing that? And the side effect: if you are blitting (plotting) an object sized f.ex. 32x32 bytes and want to triple its size, just set blitters line height to 24 (on a 8-bpl screen) and you can draw a scaled object using as much vertical blits as drawing the smaller one.  The routine could also be optimized to draw all bytes that have same value and are connected to each other at the same blit which is quite uselful for scalers. At least in theory it should be fast. 


Ok, now you all god-coders have had a good laugh. Wipe your tears and explain to me why this ain't a good idea and none won't use it ever:|


[Sasu Lintula]


---------------------------------------------------------------------
