@NODE "Mail_366" "Vs: Plotting"
From: "Sasu Lintula" <samali@utu.fi>
Subject: Vs: Plotting
Date: 	Wed, 28 Jul 1999 12:56:39 +0300
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8BIT
X-UIDL: 9caaa37751d8d41bcd5b2bc8e1000e95

Hi Anton,
>  Ok :)  Well it depends how much GFX work you want do do. If you have
>lots of things on your screen, and doing transparency work (this is
>very important for modern games), then you have to have a chunky buffer
>and C2P. There's a limit what you can do with the Blitter- to do more
>you have to use the CPU for blitting (assuming you've got an 030+.)


I agree with you about limited capabilities of the Blitter but when used to draw simple lines without calculating directions and minterms it's quite fast:)  It also gives you more cpu-time to calculate next pixels... What kind of  transparency effect you mean? If you have a halved palette (f.ex. 0-127 bright/128-255) and want to shade background it's easy to do masking operations for next texture while blitter is drawing. If the Blitter is busy after finishing calculations you can also use cpu to help in drawing. 
Ok, I know - sounds a bit desperate:) I just don't want to stop believing in this thing before I can see it's total rubbish:P
I have to see an optimised blitter line drawing routine which is a dead slow - someone??? ;)

[Sasu Lintula]
      


