@NODE "Mail_367" "Re: Plotting"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Thu, 29 Jul 1999 16:30:53 +1200
Subject: Re: Plotting
X-UIDL: 32e7d37e8d0e7f15fd3bb75945f0e49c

On 28-Jul-99, Sasu Lintula wrote:
> Hi Anton,
>> Ok :)  Well it depends how much GFX work you want do do. If you have
>> lots of things on your screen, and doing transparency work (this is
>> very important for modern games), then you have to have a chunky
>> buffer and C2P. There's a limit what you can do with the Blitter- to
>> do more you have to use the CPU for blitting (assuming you've got an
>> 030+.)

> I agree with you about limited capabilities of the Blitter but when
> used to draw simple lines without calculating directions and minterms
> it's quite fast:) It also gives you more cpu-time to calculate next
> pixels... What kind of transparency effect you mean? If you have a
> halved palette (f.ex. 0-127 bright/128-255) and want to shade
> background it's easy to do masking operations for next texture while
> blitter is drawing. If the Blitter is busy after finishing
> calculations you can also use cpu to help in drawing. Ok, I know -
> sounds a bit desperate:) I just don't want to stop believing in this
> thing before I can see it's total rubbish:P I have to see an optimised
> blitter line drawing routine which is a dead slow - someone??? ;)

  We had a good talk about this on the list earlier on - it really
depends on how much drawing you're doing, if you're just doing some
lines, the blitter way is probably fine, and efficient, but if you're
doing lots of lines, or lots of effects like smoke, fog, multiple
layers, or lots of players onscreen, shadows, texture mapping in 3D
etc, then the only way you could do that is with the CPU- the better
the CPU the more effects it can do! 

  So you'll just have to experiment :)
 
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
