@NODE "Mail_416" "Re: Random Numbers"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 04 Jul 1999 07:57:29 -0500
Subject: Re: Random Numbers
X-UIDL: bd55c802c4b61bd5b1df23095fab3991

--BOUNDARY.1748475024.1

Hi Ayar

On 03-Jul-99, Ayar Baboon wrote:
> 
> *Note* This mail for everyone who answered my mail, cheers doods!

> Hmm...
> What I did for printing the rank:
> 
> Select Int(rank). I don't know if this is equivalent?

You don't even need to do the INT() - this is automatic if you store the
returned random number in an integer variable. 
> 
> There seems to be conflict over whether 6 is included or not. This is
> what I was wondering about, and I had a feeling that 0 and 6 would be
> less likely than other values.

Try the attached test code.  You will find that over a long run, all the
numbers (including 0) will be picked more or less equally.  EXCEPT the
highest number, which is NEVER picked.

Actually, I think there is a very slight chance that it could be picked. 
But I have tried the example several times with it set to 600000 loops, and
the top number has never come up...

Later...
-- 
Facts do not cease to exist because they are ignored.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748475024.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="RandomTest.asc"

#choices=21               ;number of choices to use

Dim timesused.l(#choices)
RRandomize Ticks

For i.l = 0 To 10000      ;amount of random numbers to pick
  a.w=Rnd(#choices)
  timesused(a)+1
  If i=0
    NPrint "First pick was ",a
  EndIf
Next


For i = 0 To #choices
  NPrint i," x ",timesused(i)
Next

MouseWait
End



--BOUNDARY.1748475024.1

