@NODE "Mail_421" "Re: Random Numbers"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Mon, 05 Jul 1999 15:42:18 +1200
Subject: Re: Random Numbers
X-UIDL: 27663638a7d2b3ab6041e3011a75f0d1

On 04-Jul-99, Tony Rolfe wrote:
 
> Martin Gardner had a wonderful article in Scientific American about 20
> years ago in which he proved that, in a truly random sequence of
> numbers, the next number would be absolutely predictable!

> The logic was along the lines of "a truly random sequence has all
> numbers equally likely so that, after enough of them have been set up,
> the next one must be the one which will keep everything balanced".

> Just thought I'd mention that!

  Well, that's what those Pool predictor programs use. As far as
mathematics is concerned, it's crap, as each new number in a Random
sequence is considered a separate event, unconnected to any previous
events- this is different with Card counting in BlackJack, as previous
cards can be guaranteed not to come up till the next shuffle! 
  The above mentioned system, requires a more mystical/spiritual logic,
not a mathematical one. It comes down to your personal belief :-)

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
     


