@NODE "Mail_430" "Re: Random Numbers"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 17 Jul 1999 07:44:46 +0500
Subject: Re: Random Numbers
X-UIDL: 3eecd0e731266b416a27416dc62caa33

On 17-Jul-99, Toby Zuijdveld flashed:

>Nahhhh #Rnd#(x) is random 100% of the time (well, before ppl get technical on
>me,
>not random, just so calculated us humans can't tell the differance...)...  I
>believe #RRnd#(x) is the command that is linked to the #Randomise# command...

>And
>yeh, using a set seed value for #Randomise# would make #RRnd#(x) give the
same
>results every time.


  That's true.  In fact, for humans and machines, there is really no such
thing as a truely random action.  Everything a human does is based on
oppinions, facts, feelings, instincts, missconceptions, etc. even if it
is subconcious.  For machines, everything is purely according to the
laws of physics at some level.  We achieve an approximation of randomness
by not implimenting concious thought in a decision.  For machines, the
use of an external qualifier seed (such as a human input, a timer reading,
the temperature, wind velocity, etc.) is necessesary to best emulate real
randomness.


 cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



