> If there is only one timer, might'nt reseting it mess up other
> programs?

I think it's just for your program.  Using ResetTimer doesn't seem to hurt
any other programs.
> 
>> Statement: RRANDOMIZE 
>> *********************
>>      Syntax: RRandomize Seed
>>       Modes: Amiga or Blitz
>> Description:
>> Given a float-type expression or variable,
>> RRandomize will "seed" the
>> reproducible random number generator.  The sequence
>> of pseudo-random
>> numbers produced by "RRND" will be the same for each
>> seed given it.
>> If you require trully random numbers, try
>> "RRandomize Ticks."
>> 
> 
> Ah. I see 'RRandomize Ticks' isn't one command. You're passing 'ticks'
> as a parameter?
> So I'll get a different sequence each time...

Yeah, but it doesn't seem to work like it says :(

But see the attached example for a way that does work...
> 
>> Function: RRND 
>> **************
>>      Syntax: n=RRnd (Low,High)
>>       Modes: Amiga or Blitz
>> Description:
>> Given a range such as (1,6) this function will
>> return a random number
>> based on the seed given it by "RRandomize."  These
>> sets of "random"
>> numbers can be repeated if you provide the same
>> seed.  This can be
>> useful in games, etc. so that using "RRandomize
>> Level#" and then using
>> the RRnd() function to randomly draw the screen,
>> each time the player
>> returns to that particular level, it will be the
>> same.
> 
> If you can't be arsed designing levels ;)

I think he means that you could use it to generate different levels EACH
time the game is played by starting with a different seed - but every time
you returned to the same level during the current play, it would be the
same.
> 
> I don't understand the High,Low parameters (Sorry!!!)

It lets you specify the range of numbers to return -

RRnd (5,10) will return a number between 5 and 10 (inclusive)
RRnd (0,10) will return from 0 ~ 10, etc...

RRnd() DOES return the high number, unlike Rnd()

Later...
-- 
A bird in the hand does it on your wrist.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748883480.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="RRnd_Example.asc"

#choices=21               ;number of choices to use

;this next bit will give a random starting number

ResetTimer
NPrint "Click mouse to start"
Repeat
  VWait
Until Joyb(0)
seed.f=Ticks/.3           ;the seed must be a float
NPrint "seed is ",seed
RRandomize seed

;-------------------------------------------------

Dim timesused.l(#choices)

For i.l = 0 To 10000      ;amount of random numbers to pick
  a.w=RRnd(4,#choices)    ;low pick, high pick
  timesused(a)+1
  If i=0
    NPrint "First pick was ",a
  EndIf
Next


For i = 0 To #choices
  NPrint i," x ",timesused(i)
Next

MouseWait
End



--BOUNDARY.1748883480.1

