> However then the bottom number never gets picked..
> you are probably better
> with:
> 
> High=32
> dwell=Int(Rnd(High+1))
> 
> Are you not?

Precisly.

As the instigator of this thread (it's had a good innings!) I felt I
should be the one to say 'Stop!'. However, I've noticed some stuff ;)

Remember that quick listing Curt Esser sent? It picks a number from one
to 6 at random, and picks 10000 times.

I typed it in, but I also added some code to create a histogram.
For the line:

picknum=Rnd(6)

0 to 5 are picked quite evenly, but 6 is never picked. I upped the
loops to 95000 (much higher and the For...Next won't work), and 6 never
gets picked.

So, apart from 6, a discrete uniform distribution? (i.e. the graph is a
rectangle)

Something interesting I noted: the above line I quoted, I then changed

picknum=Rnd(Rnd(6))

What did I get? Smaller values are picked a lot more often. 5 and 6 are
never picked.

What's so interesting? Well, the histogram looks frighteningly like a
natural growth/decay curve (where y=e^x). 

Anyone want the code? I'm going to do some stuff in Blitz mode, see if
I can get some weird GFX out of it!

Regards
	James


