@NODE "Mail_447" "Random Numbers (or are they????) Good question :)"
From: Rob Hutchinson <loki@sds.in2home.co.uk>
Date: Fri, 09 Jul 1999 18:23:39 +0100
Organization: Satanic Dreams Software.
Subject: Random Numbers (or are they????) Good question :)
X-UIDL: e86bb8e70981ce97fcbec76612b8be4e

--BOUNDARY.272683888.2
Encoding: binary

Hello Mikkel
     Hiya, Mikkel... ,on 07-Jul-99 you mailed me about: Re: Random Numbers! So I`ma reply`in...

[=> Hello Rob.
[=> 
[=> You wrote:
[=> 
[=>> This will take the initial random-seed of the miggy`s CIATimer..
[=>> This is as "Random" as you`ll get it :) (I think)
[=> 
[=> Offcourse, Rnd is what is called "True Random", as opposed to the RRnd
[=> function that allows you to specify seeds, so that you will be able get
[=> the same string of random numbers each time you try. (Very usefull for
[=> generateing random levels and fractal landscapes. Worms anyone ?) :o>

Ahhhhhh, but think about RRnd.. It`s exactly the same as doing this:

<tsb>Start code.

Repeat
  Low.l = 10
  High.l = 100

  RNumber.l = Low.l+Rnd(High.l-Low.l)

  NPrint RNumber.l
  If RNumber>=100
    Stop
  EndIf

  Count+1
Until Count=1000

End

<tsb>End Code

Or is it? ehehe
Notice how 100 never gets picked.. EXACLTY like RRnd.. Never picking the
top number..

Anyway, this is what I reckon RRnd does. :)

[=> Oh, also this function is allmost useless on autobooting software.
[=> 
[=>> [=> how my Miggy does random numbers? Surely computers are too stupid
[=>> to
[=> 
[=>> It`s just a mathematical formula, basically, it has an inital number,
[=>> then it performs a mathematical calculation on it to change it.. This
[=>> means that if you use Rnd or RRnd without RRandomize, the inital /Seed/
[=>> hasn`t changed, and everytime you run your program it will pick the
[=>> numbers in exactly the same order.
[=> 
[=> Not true for the Rnd operation. It's a true random rutine and will
[=> return different values regardless of what seed you give RRandomize.
[=> Offcourse it's still a progressive iteration random number generator.

Exactly.. But see above.. :)

Attached is my NewRRnd{} function which works with longwords. :)
And uses Rnd instead of RRnd. However it doesn`t work with
decimal numbers/quicks.

[=> 
[=> Greets,
-- 

Rob,
-- 
MAILTO:loki@sds.in2home.co.uk | #ICQ:# 27181384
#FAX:# 0870 0888470 | #BBS:# Maybe later :)
#SDS FOUNDER:# URL: http://www.satanicdreams.freeserve.co.uk/
#PROJECT INFO:# Minimum Safe Distance [####------ 40% ish complete. ]
#HOME OF:# /MorrisTheMaggot, BB2MUIUpdate, TimeSwipe, NIB,/
/CTTM2, BlitzBFB, Prefs2000 & TMS. And too much other stuff./
[ Do agnostics really say, 'Oh, bother' when their planes go down? ]

--BOUNDARY.272683888.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="NewRRnd.ASC"


  Function.l NewRRnd{Low.l,High.l}

    RNumber.l = Int(Rnd(1.0)*Val(Str$(High.l-Low.l)+".0"))
    RNumber.l = Low.l+RNumber.l
    Function Return RNumber.l

  End Function

  ;##################################################################

  Repeat
    NPrint NewRRnd{10,12312314}
    Count+1
  Until Count=100

  End



--BOUNDARY.272683888.2

