@NODE "Mail_477" "Re: Run from Execute_"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 23 Jul 1999 17:47:52 -0500
Subject: Re: Run from Execute_
X-UIDL: 510cfbf98a66bde1fc740942d7a78a87

Hi Neil

On 21-Jul-99, Neil Bullock wrote:
> Hi,
> 
> I'm attempting to get the Run command to work from the Execute_ Function
> in Blitz.
> 
> e=Execute_("Run program >nil:",0,0)
> 
> Except that that doesn't work with various programs. There doesn't seem to
> be a pattern between the ones that it doesn't work with, it just doesn't
> work. If I remove the '>nil:' part, a window opens with '[CLI X]' (X being
> the process number) in it, which is something I want to surpress.
> 
> How can I go about executing a program using Run, but not get output? 

Try it like this:

cmd$="Run >NIL: "+chr$(34)+"Blah:blah/blah/myprog"+chr$(34)
;cmd$+" "+(any required arguments given in string form)

Execute_ &cmd$,0,0

The chr$(34)'s surrounding the command path/name will eliminate potential
problems with spaces in the path or command name.

> Or,
> alternatively (which is why I'm using Run in the first place) how can I
> get to run a program to it returns to the Blitz program which launched it
> rather than waiting for the program to return?

The above should do it.  Execute_ works just like typing something into a
Shell, but you must always give it the full path name of the command to be
executed.  And putting the ">NIL:" right after "Run" suppresses the new
CLI's output (preventing the window from opening) - putting it after the
command name will only suppress the command's output, but not the CLI if
you see what I mean.

Later...
-- 
"The important thing is not to stop questioning.
Question EVERYTHING."
-- Albert Einstein

