@NODE "Mail_486" "Re: screenmode type question"
Comments: Authenticated sender is <childm@vax.sbu.ac.uk>
From: "Mike Child" <mike.child@sbu.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 30 Jul 1999 10:31:30 +0000
Encoding: 7BIT
Subject: Re: screenmode type question
X-UIDL: 9983db1b174f65dfb90b350d40c5b5ec


> > What would be the difference between,
> >
> > PAL Hires Lace - on an SVGA with Scandoubler & Flickerfixer
> >
> > and a
> >
> > DBLPAL Hires on SVGA with SD but without FF
> >
> > both 640*512,256 col screens
> >
> > would they display as same or would on be more steady?
> >
> > which?
> 
> PAL Hires Lace with SD/FF will be quite stable. Is your DBLPAL Hires screenmode
> "Laced" or "No Flicker"? If its no flicker then that'll probably be more
> stable. If its laced then it'll be laced and make you go blind without the FF.

Couple more points - PAL Hires lace is a 15khz mode, artificially 
doubled up by the scan doubler - wheras Double Pal is (can't remember 
exactly) more like 30khz. This means the computer is doing more work 
for Double Pal and the display redraws slower. I use a Pal Hires 
Lace wb and with FF there is no noticable flicker at all, however, 
the display is still being updated on alternate lines each frame, the 
flicker is fixed by the ff but moving displays still get a slight 
saw-tooth effect in the changing part of the display which may or may 
not be noticable. Generally it isn`t but you can see it in Doom in 
that screen mode (which drags a bit even on 060 so I don't use it 
anyway) for example.

Also, I'm not 100% sure but I don't think my flicker fixer works on 
screenmodes that are not also scan doubled, ie. 15khz laced modes - 
are flicker fixed, but Double Pal passes through untouched so you 
isn't flicker fixed even if its laced.

regards
Mike Child

