  Yes, I've been thinking about it :) I'd have to find out how to code a
system library as I haven't done one before. I'd have to do it in
assem, as I don't know C, but it'd be preferable in assem for speed
anyway.
   It wouldn't be too hard as I'm making the Blitz interface quite
independant anyhow- I'm about to make an array of data to be sent on
login, so you can easily customise things like player preferences to be
sent/received to/from Server, or any other data you wanted (even stuff
like sound samples, narrator device settings etc). I'd just need to
have Init and Exit calls, to allocate the data space for each program
using the lib- your program would be given a pointer to it's own
allocated data space with the Init call.
  
> Of course it would be better to finish those functions before turning
> it in to a library, so that the translation would be as bug free as it
> possibly can.
> And the translator would only need to bother from the bugs he/she made
> while converting it.

  Yes, this is the reason I haven't bothered so far, as I've still got a
lot to do, and it's /much/ harder to debug than a single-user program.
Some bugs only show up with certain timings between programs, and are
hard to repeat- obviously you have to make sure your logic is
rock-solid instead! :-)  And debugging assem later in such an
environment would be horrible as well!! 
  It might not be so bad if I could just update the library calls that
had been changed, and leave the rest intact, so I could still develop
the Funcs in Blitz and then re-do the assem calls when I'm happy with
the new versions.

