@NODE "Mail_569" "Urgent Press Release regarding UCM"
From: "Neil Bullock" <i03427@trogsoft.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Urgent Press Release regarding UCM
Date: Wed, 14 Jul 1999 17:26:44 +0100
	charset="Windows-1252"
Encoding: 7bit
X-Info: Selby College, England
X-UIDL: bac5e8e5ae53f482b45ee1c15fc821e5

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE - URGENT

While creating a keyfile for someone who recently registered UCM, I noticed
that this person had entered '9999999' as their phone number. This is
obviously not their real phone number, but works all the same. This person's
name began with an N and they lived in a town whose first letter was H.

The program which creates keyfiles for UCM users works on a batch basis. When
someone submitted their registration form, the information was presented to me
in a specific way. I put this information into one large file, and give it to
the keyfile creator. The keyfile program takes this information and
automatically creates keyfiles, which I then send out.

However, people who didn't want to give out their details such as phone number
and town they live in could have had problems. If you made up a phone number
which was as simple as '9999999', it's likely that some other people could
have done the same meaning that 3 digits in their registration number would be
the same.

This is not the problem. The problem arises when you take into account the
town a person lives in. Whether this is made up or not, if it begins with the
same letter as someone elses town who used a simple made up phone number, then
the last 6, 7 or 8 digits of the registration number will be the same.

The problem is compounded by the fact that if the first letter of someone's
first name is the same as the first letter of someone elses (pretty common)
then they will have the same registration number. This is something which
needs to be sorted out since the next release of UCM will not work with
duplicate registration numbers.

I know of several people on this list who have registered UCM, and as such, I
would like to ask them to go to http://web.ukonline.co.uk/masterorg/ucm.htm
and fill in the form at the bottom of the page. You'll need your
UCM:Data/Keyfile.dat file handy.

=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
  T R O G L A D I T E  -  S O F T W A R E
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
     __       Senior Manager - Neil Bullock
