@NODE "Mail_596" "Wierd multitasking prob"
From: "Vic E Babes" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
        "Neil Bullock" <trogladite@trogsoft.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Wierd multitasking prob
Date: Tue, 20 Jul 1999 18:55:20 +0100
	charset="Windows-1252"
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 608e11c975a3256b838a441fb29c63b0

Hello, ppl,

I finished the updated version of my speech GUI a week ago, but it has
taken me that long to find out why a certain inconsistent bug occurred.

Now that I've determined the cause of the error, I'd like to know if
anyone on this list can explain why it happens.  The problem is as
follows:

The user enters sentences in a string gadget.
These sentences are stored in a listview.
When 'auto speak' is switched on, the program automatically speaks the
  sentence when the user clicks on a sentence in the listview.  The
  code for which, looks a bit like this.

---------------

* Gosub speaksentence
  GTSetString <human sentence string gadget>,<selected sentence>
  GTSetString <translated string gadget>,<selected sentence>
  GTSetString <info gadget>,<current sentence 'of' number of sentences>
  If the sentence is the bottom visible in the listview, scroll listview
    up one place.
^

.speaksentence
  If autospeak
    If Manual Then PhoneticSpeak(trans$) Else Speak(phrase$)
  Endif
Return

----------------

Now this works fine when using the Speak command when using a MODE of
NATURAL, or ROBOT.  But if the MODE is MANUAL, I have to use the
PhoneticSpeak command, and the sentence was not being spoken - I found
out that the reason for this, was because I had to move the line above
that is marked with * to the line marked with ^.

Now since the Amiga is a multi-tasking machine, why is the speech cut-off
when Intuition is updating the gadgets?  Especially since the narrator
is given a priority of 100 whilst it is speaking?

I'm quite happy moving the offending line, but when I was writing the
program, I thought it would be better to have an immediate response to
the mouseclick, and that Intuition could update the gadgets whilst the
sentence was being spoken.  I just felt it would be more user-friendly.

What's more confusing, is that the Speak command works perfectly - but
the speak command requires that the sentence be passed for translation,
and that the translation then be sent to the narrator - whereas the
PhoneticSpeak just sends the translated string direct to the narrator,
which should be faster!

Any ideas?

VIC




